<div style=position:absolute;top:1436;left:0><hr><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td bgcolor=eeeeee align=right><font face=arial,sans-serif><a name=2><b>Page 2</b></a></font></td></tr></table></div><font size=4 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:23px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1667;left:88><nobr>Review of studies on the public–private partnerships (PPP)</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1697;left:262><nobr>for infrastructure projects</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 face=Times><span style=font-size:17px;font-family:Times>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1745;left:217><nobr>Caiyun Cui</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:10px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1741;left:311><nobr><a href=""></a>a<font color=#000000>,</font><a href=""></a>b<font color=#000000>,</font><font style=font-size:15px><a href="">⁎</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:17px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1745;left:344><nobr><a href=""></a>, <font color=#000000>Yong Liu</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:10px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1741;left:435><nobr><a href=""></a>c</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 face=Times><span style=font-size:17px;font-family:Times>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1745;left:442><nobr>, Alex Hope</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:10px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1741;left:543><nobr><a href=""></a>d</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 face=Times><span style=font-size:17px;font-family:Times>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1745;left:551><nobr><a href=""></a>, Jianping Wang</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:10px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1741;left:684><nobr><a href=""></a>a</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:5px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1778;left:177><nobr>a <i><font style=font-size:9px>School of Mechanics and Civil Engineering, China University of Mining and Technology, Xuzhou 221116, China</font></i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1793;left:269><nobr>b <i><font style=font-size:9px>North China Institute of Science and Technology, Langfang 065201, China</font></i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1808;left:203><nobr>c <i><font style=font-size:9px>School of Civil Engineering and Architecture, Zhejiang Sci-Tech University, Hangzhou 310018, China</font></i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1822;left:295><nobr>d <i><font style=font-size:9px>Northumbria University, Newcastle upon Tyne, United Kingdom</font></i></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1864;left:230><nobr>Received 18 July 2017; received in revised form 23 February 2018; accepted 12 March 2018</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1879;left:401><nobr>Available online xxxx</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:11px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1947;left:64><nobr><b>Abstract</b></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1980;left:82><nobr>Public–private partnership (PPP) is an approach adopted to enhance the economic value of infrastructure outputs, and it encompasses a broad</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1996;left:64><nobr>spectrum of public sector infrastructure. Many researchers have explored the application of PPP to improve the efficiency of infrastructure delivery.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2013;left:64><nobr>This study aims to review the existing PPP research to explore the status quo, trends, and gaps in research for PPP infrastructure projects.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2029;left:64><nobr>A systematic process involving a three-phase word frequency analysis, cluster analysis, and a search on potential research topics helps to provide</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2045;left:64><nobr>enough potential articles related to PPP research and reduce arbitrariness and subjectivity involved in the research topic analysis. As a result, six</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2062;left:64><nobr>main research topics aligned with the infrastructure PPP projects were derived. The research gaps and research directions can serve as a motivation</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2078;left:64><nobr>for researchers and practitioners to work on the next generation of PPP studies to support the development of infrastructure.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2095;left:64><nobr>© 2018 Elsevier Ltd. APM and IPMA. All rights reserved.</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2127;left:64><nobr><i>Keywords: </i>Public–private-partnerships (PPP); Infrastructure; Build-operate-transfer (BOT); Private finance initiative (PFI); Cluster analysis; Word cloud</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2193;left:64><nobr><b>1. Introduction</b></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2228;left:82><nobr>Public–private partnerships (PPP) are widely used to deliver</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2246;left:64><nobr>a series of infrastructure projects in the world. The PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2264;left:64><nobr>approach increases the economic value of infrastructure outputs</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2282;left:64><nobr>(<font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Zhang, 2005</a></font>) and facilitates the overall development of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2300;left:64><nobr>infrastructure (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Li et al., 2016b</a></font><a href=#21></a>), such as the establishment of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2318;left:64><nobr>transportation infrastructure, sports facilities, water conservancy</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2336;left:64><nobr>facilities, and waste-to-energy plants. Alongside the rapidly</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2354;left:64><nobr>increasing application of PPP, research interest in the topic has</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2372;left:64><nobr>also surged during the last two decades, leading to significant</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2389;left:64><nobr>growth in the number of published articles as well as in the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2407;left:64><nobr>diversity of research topics, domains, and methods. The</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2425;left:64><nobr>development of the academic body of knowledge on PPP has</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2192;left:467><nobr>enabled researchers to share research findings and explore the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2210;left:467><nobr>status quo and trends about the PPP practice; thus, this analysis</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2228;left:467><nobr>of articles published in academic journals will assist researchers</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2246;left:467><nobr>in exploring the current status and future trends of the chosen</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2264;left:467><nobr>topics in this area (<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Ke et al., 2009</a></font>).</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2282;left:485><nobr><a href=#21>Ke et al. (2009) </a><font color=#231f20>analysed 170 studies conducted over the</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2300;left:467><nobr>period 1998–2008 selected from the following academic journals:</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2318;left:467><nobr>Construction Management and Economics (CME), International</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2336;left:467><nobr>Journal of Project Management (IJPM), Engineering, Construction</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2354;left:467><nobr>and Architectural Management (ECAM), Journal of Construction</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2372;left:467><nobr>Engineering and Management (JCEM), Journal of Management</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2389;left:467><nobr>in Engineering (JME), Proceedings of Institution of Civil</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2407;left:467><nobr>Engineers—Civil Engineering(PICE-CE), and Public Money</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2425;left:467><nobr>and Management (PMM). The results of their study showed that</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2443;left:467><nobr>the three traditional topics—risk, procurement, and financing—</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2461;left:467><nobr>have been expanded over the years to include the following</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2479;left:467><nobr>seven research topic categories: investment environment, pro-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2497;left:467><nobr>curement, economic viability, financial package, risk management,</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2479;left:69><nobr>⁎ Corresponding author.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2499;left:81><nobr><i>E-mail address: </i><font color=#2e3192><a href=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=vi&amp;prev=_t&amp;sl=auto&amp;tl=vi&amp;u=http://200800890ccy%40ncist.edu.cn>200800890ccy@ncist.edu.cn </a></font>(C. Cui).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1603;left:678><nobr>www.elsevier.com/locate/ijproman</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2540;left:64><nobr><a href=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=vi&amp;prev=_t&amp;sl=auto&amp;tl=vi&amp;u=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004>https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004</a></nobr></div>
</span></font>

</span></font>

<div style=position:absolute;top:1480;left:64><nobr>JPMA-02118; No of Pages 22</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1736;left:310><nobr><a href="" style="background-color:#0000ff;padding:19px 8px;"></a></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1736;left:310><nobr><a href="" style="background-color:#0000ff;padding:19px 8px;"></a></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1736;left:322><nobr><a href="" style="background-color:#0000ff;padding:19px 9px;"></a></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1736;left:322><nobr><a href="" style="background-color:#0000ff;padding:19px 9px;"></a></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1736;left:434><nobr><a href="" style="background-color:#0000ff;padding:19px 8px;"></a></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1736;left:434><nobr><a href="" style="background-color:#0000ff;padding:19px 8px;"></a></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1736;left:542><nobr><a href="" style="background-color:#0000ff;padding:19px 9px;"></a></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1736;left:683><nobr><a href="" style="background-color:#0000ff;padding:19px 8px;"></a></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1736;left:683><nobr><a href="" style="background-color:#0000ff;padding:19px 8px;"></a></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1588;left:258><nobr><a href=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=vi&amp;prev=_t&amp;sl=auto&amp;tl=vi&amp;u=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004 style="background-color:#0000ff;padding:12px 296px;"></a></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1588;left:258><nobr><a href=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=vi&amp;prev=_t&amp;sl=auto&amp;tl=vi&amp;u=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004 style="background-color:#0000ff;padding:12px 314px;"></a></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1508;left:687><nobr><a href="Journal logo" style="background-color:#0000ff;padding:90px 157px;"></a></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:1508;left:64><nobr><a href="Imprint logo" style="background-color:#0000ff;padding:90px 80px;"></a></nobr></div>

<div style=position:absolute;top:2626;left:0><hr><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td bgcolor=eeeeee align=right><font face=arial,sans-serif><a name=3><b>Page 3</b></a></font></td></tr></table></div><font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2739;left:49><nobr>governance issues, and integration research. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Marsilio et al. (2011)</a></font></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2757;left:49><nobr>used bibliometric techniques (citation and co-citation analysis)</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2775;left:49><nobr>to analyse articles over the period 1990–2010 from the Social</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2793;left:49><nobr>Sciences Citation Index (SSCI) database. Finally, four main</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2810;left:49><nobr>clusters were identified—governmental and intergovernmental</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2828;left:49><nobr>organizations (IGOs), public administration and public policy</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2846;left:49><nobr>academics, scholars studying transaction cost and contract</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2864;left:49><nobr>theory, and scholars studying strategy and alliance/network</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2882;left:49><nobr>theory. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Andon (2012) </a></font>presented an analysis of relevant PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2900;left:49><nobr>literature published up to December 2010 and proposed five</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2918;left:49><nobr>research themes that are appropriate for the current PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2936;left:49><nobr>research. These themes include the nature of and rationale for</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2954;left:49><nobr>PPPs, processes and procedures encouraging the decision-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2972;left:49><nobr>making for undertaking PPPs, processes and procedures for ex-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2990;left:49><nobr>post evaluations of PPPs, merit and worth of PPPs, and PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3008;left:49><nobr>regulation and guidance. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Neto et al. (2016) </a></font>used bibliometric</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3026;left:49><nobr>methods to study 575 articles related to PPP and its variant, the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3044;left:49><nobr>public finance initiative (PFI), from the Web of Science citation</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3061;left:49><nobr>indexing service. Their analysis suggests that PPP research</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3079;left:49><nobr>has been focusing on a limited set of topics, which includes</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3097;left:49><nobr>contract performance, qualitative costs and benefits, contract</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3115;left:49><nobr>design and risk sharing, political and institutional issues, and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3133;left:49><nobr>tests on value for money. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Chen et al. (2016) </a></font>analysed 95</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3151;left:49><nobr>empirical studies examining the influence of PPP data on</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3169;left:49><nobr>respective research themes through a meta-analysis. As a result,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3187;left:49><nobr>PPP research topics were classified into the following five</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3205;left:49><nobr>categories: performance, contract, risk, value for money, and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3223;left:49><nobr>institutional factors.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3241;left:67><nobr>Each of these studies has significantly contributed towards</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3259;left:49><nobr>summarizing the PPP research history, reviewing the status</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3277;left:49><nobr>quo, and outlining trends of research in this area. Concerning</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3295;left:49><nobr>the research methods employed, counting or scientometric</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3313;left:49><nobr>methods are used by each of these studies to summarize the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3330;left:49><nobr>publication year, journal title, research area, research origin,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3348;left:49><nobr>and geographic scope, among others. Despite their useful</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3366;left:49><nobr>contributions, most of these studies rely on subjective judgment</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3384;left:49><nobr>in their assessments of status quo and research trends. To</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3402;left:49><nobr>reduce the possibility for misinterpretations and misunder-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3420;left:49><nobr>standings among researchers, it is essential to conduct a new</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3438;left:49><nobr>objective review of the scientific literature on PPP to derive</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3456;left:49><nobr>the current research status and thematic trends. In this study,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3474;left:49><nobr>word frequency and cluster analyses were implemented as a</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3492;left:49><nobr>means to classify research topics effectively to reduce the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3510;left:49><nobr>arbitrariness involved in previous studies (<a href=#23></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Zhou et al., 2016</a></font>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3528;left:49><nobr>Compared to other methods, the word frequency analysis can</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3546;left:49><nobr>provide greater prominence quantitatively to words that appear</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3564;left:49><nobr>more frequently in a source (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Riggs and Hu, 2013</a></font><a href=#22></a>). Meanwhile,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3582;left:49><nobr>cluster analysis is used to record and categorise specific</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3599;left:49><nobr>phenomena in a systematic and quantitative way to reflect the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3617;left:49><nobr>main features of prior literature. In addition, an analysis of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3635;left:49><nobr>research gaps has been afforded limited attention in the extant</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3653;left:49><nobr>literature, and yet may act as an important guide for researchers</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3671;left:49><nobr>seeking to expand the body of knowledge. Considering the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3689;left:49><nobr>increasing development of PPP in construction and infrastruc-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3707;left:49><nobr>ture, this study aims to provide a more objective overview of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3725;left:49><nobr>existing PPP research and explore potential research gaps and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3743;left:49><nobr>research directions.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2739;left:453><nobr><b>2. Methodology</b></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2775;left:470><nobr>Due to a reduction in the arbitrariness involved in such</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2793;left:453><nobr>studies, quantitative statistics was employed to determine the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2810;left:453><nobr>number of publications in journals, years, geographical areas,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2828;left:453><nobr>and PPP types. The word frequency and cluster analyses were</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2846;left:453><nobr>implemented as the foundations for classifying research topics</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2864;left:453><nobr>because of their suitability for research. Subsequently, word</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2882;left:453><nobr>frequency analyses were conducted based on word clouds (or</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2900;left:453><nobr>tag clouds). Compared to other methods, one of its advantages</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2918;left:453><nobr>is that word clouds are graphical representations of word</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2936;left:453><nobr>frequency that provide greater prominence to words that appear</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2954;left:453><nobr>more frequently in a source (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Riggs and Hu, 2013</a></font>). In addition,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2972;left:453><nobr>cluster analysis, which is used to record and categorise specific</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2990;left:453><nobr>phenomena systematically to reflect the main features of prior</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3008;left:453><nobr>literature, is used to visualise grouping of sources that share</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3026;left:453><nobr>similar words or attribute values.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3044;left:470><nobr>Thus, the review analysis provided a comprehensive dis-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3061;left:453><nobr>closure of PPP applications and ensured that the results of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3079;left:453><nobr>this study are reliable and valid. This study also employed</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3097;left:453><nobr>a systematic process to review the existing PPP research</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3115;left:453><nobr>literature on infrastructure projects and to explore research gaps</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3133;left:453><nobr>and suggestions for future study. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#4>Fig. 1 </a></font>divides the research</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3151;left:453><nobr>framework into a two-stage process. A comprehensive literature</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3169;left:453><nobr>search and a systematic coding process of articles relevant to the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3187;left:453><nobr>PPP infrastructure projects was conducted in Stage 1, and an</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3205;left:453><nobr>analysis of filtered articles was conducted in Stage 2 to analyse</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3223;left:453><nobr>research topics, explore research gaps, and research directions.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3241;left:453><nobr>The flow of the overall research framework of the current study</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3259;left:453><nobr>comprises the following six steps.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3277;left:470><nobr>The six research steps are as follows:</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3313;left:453><nobr>Step 1 Determining the academic databases that can be used</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3330;left:498><nobr>for article search and selection: To conduct a compre-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3348;left:498><nobr>hensive review of previous researches in a research</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3366;left:498><nobr>area, a methodical selection of journals in academic</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3384;left:498><nobr>databases is necessary (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Osei-Kyei and Chan, 2015</a></font><a href=#22></a>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3402;left:498><nobr>Databases used for bibliometric techniques usually</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3420;left:498><nobr>come from different sources. One objective way to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3438;left:498><nobr>identify different source documents is to select journals</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3456;left:498><nobr>and studies in a broader scope (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Marsilio et al., 2011</a></font><a href=#21></a>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3474;left:498><nobr>Before determining the academic databases used for</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3492;left:498><nobr>article search and selection, and as an initial screening</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3510;left:498><nobr>process, pre-search was carried out to ensure that the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3528;left:498><nobr>selected academic databases are reasonable. The result</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3546;left:498><nobr>of pre-search showed the Web of Science to be an</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3564;left:498><nobr>appropriate option because it included articles in a</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3582;left:498><nobr>broader scope. However, the Web of Science did not</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3599;left:498><nobr>provide complete information of several PPP studies</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3617;left:498><nobr>in some reputable journals such as CME and ECAM.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3635;left:498><nobr>Therefore, other database and journals should be</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3653;left:498><nobr>affiliated with publishers to facilitate a comprehensive</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3671;left:498><nobr>article search. As the largest and the most important</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3689;left:498><nobr>publisher of civil engineering knowledge, the American</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3707;left:498><nobr>Society of Civil Engineers (ASCE) includes several</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3725;left:498><nobr>important studies on the construction and infrastructure</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:3743;left:498><nobr>industry. Additionally, most of the reputable journals</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2698;left:49><nobr>2</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:2698;left:250><nobr><i>C. Cui et al. / International Journal of Project Management xx (2018) xxx</i>–<i>xxx</i></nobr></div>

<div style=position:absolute;top:4718;left:110><nobr>Francis, which also have important positions in the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4736;left:110><nobr>construction management and infrastructure industry.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4753;left:110><nobr>Therefore, and referring to the databases scope adopted</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4771;left:110><nobr>by <font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Zhou et al. (2016)</a></font><a href=#23></a>, Emerald, Elsevier, Taylor</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4789;left:110><nobr>&amp; Francis, and ASCE were added to the search</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4807;left:110><nobr>scope together with the Web of Science. Consequently,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4825;left:110><nobr>five academic databases—the Web of Science, ASCE</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4843;left:110><nobr>Library, Emerald, Elsevier-Science Direct, and Taylor</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4861;left:110><nobr>&amp; Francis—were selected for the literature search due to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4879;left:110><nobr>their comprehensive coverage, among relevant journals;</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4897;left:110><nobr>this selection is different from <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Osei-Kyei and Chan's</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4915;left:110><nobr><a href=#22>(2015) </a><font color=#231f20>and </font><a href=#21>Ke et al.'s (2009) </a><font color=#231f20>search scope as it confines</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4933;left:110><nobr>to specific journals.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4700;left:467><nobr>Step 2 Formulating article selection criteria and identifying</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4718;left:515><nobr>used articles: The acronym ‘PPP’, which is widely</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4736;left:515><nobr>and frequently used worldwide, was mentioned in the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4753;left:515><nobr>literature in different forms as per <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Neto et al. (2016)</a></font><a href=#22></a>;</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4771;left:515><nobr>some of the references to PPP include public-private</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4789;left:515><nobr>partnerships, PPP, and its variants including the PFI and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4807;left:515><nobr>build-operate-transfer (BOT) procurement methods.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4825;left:515><nobr>Comprehensive search words that were related to PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4843;left:515><nobr>were public-private partnership, private finance initia-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4861;left:515><nobr>tive, build operate transfer, privatised infrastructure,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4879;left:515><nobr>and privately financed, among others. Meanwhile, the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4897;left:515><nobr>search was further limited to the ‘infrastructure’ subject</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4915;left:515><nobr>area. Through pre-search, a limited number of articles</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4933;left:515><nobr>were found with the word ‘infrastructure’ in the title,</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:4663;left:349><nobr>Fig. 1. Flow of overall research framework.</nobr></div>

<div style=position:absolute;top:5006;left:0><hr><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td bgcolor=eeeeee align=right><font face=arial,sans-serif><a name=5><b>Page 5</b></a></font></td></tr></table></div><font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5119;left:97><nobr>abstract, and keywords. In order to broaden the search</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5137;left:97><nobr>scope of literature, studies with these specific terms</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5155;left:97><nobr>were found to have a relationship with PPP in the title,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5173;left:97><nobr>abstract, or keywords. Additionally, studies with the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5190;left:97><nobr>word ‘infrastructure’ expanding to the full text were</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5208;left:97><nobr>considered to meet the requirements of this study. Thus,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5226;left:97><nobr>the following search schema was adopted:</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5244;left:97><nobr>TITLE-ABS-KEY (“public private partnership” OR</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5258;left:97><nobr>“public private partnerships” OR “build operate transfer”</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5280;left:97><nobr>OR “build-operate-transfer” OR “build/operate/transfer”</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5298;left:97><nobr>OR “private finance initiative” OR “transfer operate</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5316;left:97><nobr>transfer” OR “build own operate” OR “build own operate</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5334;left:97><nobr>transfer” OR “build transfer operate” OR “reconstruct</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5352;left:97><nobr>operate transfer” OR “PFI” OR “BOT” OR “PPP” OR</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5366;left:97><nobr>“BOO” OR “BOOT” OR “BTO” OR “TOT” OR “ROT”)</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5388;left:97><nobr>AND FULL-TEXT (“infrastructure”) AND (LIMIT-TO</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5406;left:97><nobr>(LANGUAGE, “English”)).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5424;left:49><nobr>Step 3 Determining article coding method and coding filtered</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5441;left:94><nobr>articles: The titles, keywords, and abstracts were used</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5459;left:94><nobr>to code the articles for further analysis. Concerning</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5477;left:94><nobr>articles wherein abstracts do not provide adequate details,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5495;left:94><nobr>the full-texts of the articles were used for coding. The</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5513;left:94><nobr>information used in the analysis comprises the following:</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5531;left:94><nobr>the title of the study, publication year, journal title,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5549;left:94><nobr>country or region where the studies were conducted,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5567;left:94><nobr>project types, and disciplines. The results of the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5585;left:94><nobr>preliminary search are shown in <font color=#2e3192><a href=#5>Table 1</a></font><a href=#5></a>. After the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5603;left:94><nobr>removal of repetitive articles, articles published under the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5621;left:94><nobr>broad categories of ‘editorial’, ‘book review’, ‘discus-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5639;left:94><nobr>sions and closures’, ‘letter to the editor’, and ‘articles in</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5657;left:94><nobr>press’ were also excluded from the analysis. The resulting</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5675;left:94><nobr>754 journal and conference articles were screened out.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5693;left:94><nobr>The results of the coding process of these articles are</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5710;left:94><nobr>showed in <font color=#2e3192><a href=#5>Section 3</a></font><a href=#5></a>, titled ‘Overview of PPP Research’.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5728;left:49><nobr>Step 4 Producing an overview of PPP studies: An overview</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5746;left:95><nobr>of PPP researches was carried out in detail under the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5764;left:95><nobr>following categories: number of publications per year,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5782;left:95><nobr>publication journal title, publications distributed by</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5800;left:95><nobr>country or region, publications distributed by project</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5818;left:95><nobr>type, and publications distributed by different disciplines.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5836;left:49><nobr>Step 5 Identifying the research topics: The word frequency and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5854;left:93><nobr>cluster analyses were implemented as foundations for</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5872;left:93><nobr>classifying research topics to reduce the arbitrariness</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5890;left:93><nobr>involved in such studies. As a result, six research topics</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5908;left:93><nobr>were identified and relationships between different</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5926;left:93><nobr>topics were analysed. To decrease the arbitrariness and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5944;left:93><nobr>subjectivity involved in the identification of research</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5119;left:496><nobr>topics, the qualitative research software, NVivo, was</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5137;left:496><nobr>utilised to calculate the word frequency and conduct</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5155;left:496><nobr>clustering analysis between the words used in the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5173;left:496><nobr>abstracts of the filtered articles in the step 3. Large</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5190;left:496><nobr>amounts of unstructured data should be dealt with in</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5208;left:496><nobr>the review analysis; this poses several technical and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5226;left:496><nobr>conceptual challenges for researchers. The software</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5244;left:496><nobr>NVivo was adopted as a research instrument when</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5262;left:496><nobr>performing qualitative research to help researchers</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5280;left:496><nobr>address the challenges faced during the review analysis.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5298;left:496><nobr>Although the software CiteSpace also offers benefits</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5316;left:496><nobr>when conducting a review of a typical research topic</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5334;left:496><nobr>through co-citation and the pathfinder algorithm,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5352;left:496><nobr>occasionally the visual output data in CiteSpace is basic,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5370;left:496><nobr>and hence does not consider useful information (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Chen,</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5388;left:496><nobr><a href=#20>2009</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#20></a>). In comparison, NVivo not only shows output data</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5406;left:496><nobr>comprehensively but also helps to think about the data</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5424;left:496><nobr>and manage ideas, thereby exploring relationships in</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5441;left:496><nobr>the data and finding emergent concepts, which are more</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5459;left:496><nobr>suitable for this study (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Brandão and Miguez, 2016</a></font><a href=#20></a>). It</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5477;left:496><nobr>can be a crucial resource when the researcher, during</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5495;left:496><nobr>qualitative research or content analysis, wants to under-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5513;left:496><nobr>stand coding categories a-priori based on the research</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5531;left:496><nobr>question, clustering comments under similarity themes,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5549;left:496><nobr>and writing descriptive explanation summarizing each</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5567;left:496><nobr>theme.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5585;left:453><nobr>Step 6 Identifying the research gaps and research directions:</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5603;left:499><nobr>In this context, a clustering algorithm guided by the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5621;left:499><nobr>Pearson correlation coefficient is used to generate a</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5639;left:499><nobr>dendrogram or cluster tree. A research gaps framework</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5657;left:499><nobr>is set up based on research topics, research gaps and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5675;left:499><nobr>future directions were identified in this Step.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5711;left:453><nobr><b>3. Overview of PPP research</b></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5746;left:453><nobr><i>3.1. Number of publications per year</i></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5782;left:470><nobr><a href=#22>Tiong (1990) </a><font color=#231f20>analysed six projects and showed that the BOT</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5800;left:453><nobr>concept, which intrigues common interest among the govern-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5818;left:453><nobr>ment, sponsors, lenders, investors, and contractors, is viable</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5836;left:453><nobr>even for large infrastructure projects. Subsequently from 1990</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5854;left:453><nobr>to 2000, Tiong and his team played a fundamental role in the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5872;left:453><nobr>development of BOT research. As observed in <font color=#2e3192><a href=#6>Table 2</a></font><a href=#6></a>, the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5890;left:453><nobr>study titled ‘CSF in competitive tendering and negotiation</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5908;left:453><nobr>model for BOT projects’ (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Tiong, 1996</a></font><a href=#22></a>) is cited most, with the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5926;left:453><nobr>number of citations peaking at 214. As outlined in <font color=#2e3192><a href=#6>Table 3</a></font>, the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5944;left:453><nobr>number of publications concerning PPP witnessed an increase</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5962;left:453><nobr>from 2006 onwards. The explosive growth of articles occurred</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5980;left:453><nobr>in 2010 and peaked in 2015, with 109 articles. The increase in</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:5997;left:453><nobr>the number of PPP studies is related to the increased application</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6015;left:453><nobr>of PPP in infrastructure in the recent years. However, despite</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6033;left:453><nobr>the rapid development of PPP research and its application,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6051;left:453><nobr>the knowledge in this domain is still at a nascent stage due</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6069;left:453><nobr>to continued instances of significant cost overturns, schedule</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6087;left:453><nobr>delays in several major PPP projects (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Love et al., 2015</a></font><a href=#21></a>),</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6105;left:453><nobr>and several governments seeking to develop models to deliver</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6123;left:453><nobr>sustainability outcomes (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Villalba-Romero et al., 2015</a></font><a href=#22></a>). Therefore,</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>

<div style=position:absolute;top:6196;left:0><hr><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td bgcolor=eeeeee align=right><font face=arial,sans-serif><a name=6><b>Page 6</b></a></font></td></tr></table></div><font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6702;left:64><nobr>it is necessary for researchers to sustain their efforts in the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6720;left:64><nobr>research of PPP and related topics.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6774;left:64><nobr><i>3.2. Publication journal title</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6810;left:82><nobr>The diffusion of PPP research studies published in journals</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6828;left:64><nobr>and conferences is numerous and scattered. Therefore, <font color=#2e3192><a href=#6>Table 4</a></font></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6846;left:64><nobr>only illustrated the distribution of the journals that published at</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6864;left:64><nobr>least 10 studies on PPP, a total of 375 journal studies. The two</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6882;left:64><nobr>journals titles that publish most studies on PPP are the Journal</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6900;left:64><nobr>of Construction Engineering and Management (ASCE), with 81</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6918;left:64><nobr>studies published on the subject, and the International Journal of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6936;left:64><nobr>Project Management, with 72 studies published on the subject.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6954;left:64><nobr>Other journals that include studies on PPP are the Journal of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6971;left:64><nobr>Management in Engineering (JME, 39), the Research in</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6989;left:64><nobr>Transportation Economics (RTE, 26), Built Environment</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7007;left:64><nobr>Project and Asset Management (BEPAM, 25), Procedia-Social</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7025;left:64><nobr>and Behavioral Sciences (PSBS, 22), the International Journal</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7043;left:64><nobr>of Public Sector Management (IJPSM, 19), and Engineering,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7061;left:64><nobr>Construction and Architectural Management (ECAM, 16). The</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7079;left:64><nobr>remaining publications have published less than 15 studies as</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7097;left:64><nobr>shown in <font color=#2e3192><a href=#6>Table 4</a></font><a href=#6></a>.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6631;left:467><nobr><i>3.3. Publications distributed by country or region</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6667;left:485><nobr>The 754 reviewed studies originate from 56 different</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6685;left:467><nobr>countries and regions covering six continents. All the articles</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6703;left:467><nobr>with co-authors originating from different countries and regions</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6721;left:467><nobr>were considered in the research origin location as shown in</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6739;left:467><nobr><a href=#7>Fig. 2</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#7></a>. A total of 165 articles originated in China as the country</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6757;left:467><nobr>witnessed a rapid development of the application of PPP in</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6775;left:467><nobr>recent years. The UK has produced 108 studies on the subject,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6793;left:467><nobr>as one of the primary destinations that led to the emergence</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6811;left:467><nobr>of the PPP concept. Other notable countries or regions with a</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6829;left:467><nobr>significant number of studies are the USA (84), Australia (80),</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6847;left:467><nobr>and India (40); all these countries contribute more than 30</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6865;left:467><nobr>articles on PPP. Compared to the findings of <font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Ke et al. (2009)</a></font>,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6883;left:467><nobr>we find that the mainland of China, India, Italy, Portugal, and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6900;left:467><nobr>Belgium have made rapid progress in PPP studies in recent</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6918;left:467><nobr>years. The rank of India's academic output advanced from the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6936;left:467><nobr>9th position in 2009 to the 5th position, putting the country</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6954;left:467><nobr>ahead of Hong Kong, Taiwan, and Singapore. Portugal and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6972;left:467><nobr>Belgium produce produced 22 and 19 articles, respectively,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:6990;left:467><nobr>which exceeded many other countries. These findings coincide</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7008;left:467><nobr>with previous studies, indicating that the UK, China (including</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7026;left:467><nobr>Hong Kong and Taiwan), Australia, the USA, India, Italy,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7044;left:467><nobr>Singapore, and Germany play leading roles in the field of PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7062;left:467><nobr>research.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7080;left:485><nobr>Recent research also reveals variations in PPP implementa-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7098;left:467><nobr>tion between developed and developing countries. Compared to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7116;left:467><nobr>developed countries, developing countries face more obstacles,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7134;left:467><nobr>such as the shortage of government financial resources, public</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7152;left:467><nobr>sector inefficiencies, huge uncertainties in contractual environ-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7170;left:467><nobr>ment, public and private partners’ capacity deficiencies, weak</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7187;left:467><nobr>political willingness, and administrative bottlenecks (<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Kwofie</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7205;left:467><nobr><a href=#21>et al., 2015</a><font color=#231f20>; </font><a href=#20>Babatunde et al., 2015</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#20></a>). These obstacles have</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7223;left:467><nobr>posed challenges in drafting complete contractual agreements</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7241;left:467><nobr>to cover all contingencies and achieve value for money in PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7259;left:467><nobr>projects (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Appuhami and Perera, 2016</a></font>). However, PPPs are more</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7277;left:467><nobr>appropriate for developing countries because such countries</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7295;left:467><nobr>can benefit more from the access to new capital and technical</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7313;left:467><nobr>expertise brought in by a PPP (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Gordon, 2012</a></font>). The private</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>

<div style=position:absolute;top:7349;left:73><nobr>Please cite this article as: C. Cui, et al., 2018. Review of studies on the public–private partnerships (PPP) for infrastructure projects, Int. J. Proj. Manag. <font color=#2e3192><a href=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=vi&amp;prev=_t&amp;sl=auto&amp;tl=vi&amp;u=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004>https://doi.org/</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7363;left:73><nobr><a href=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=vi&amp;prev=_t&amp;sl=auto&amp;tl=vi&amp;u=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004>10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004</a></nobr></div>
</span></font>

<div style=position:absolute;top:7386;left:0><hr><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td bgcolor=eeeeee align=right><font face=arial,sans-serif><a name=7><b>Page 7</b></a></font></td></tr></table></div><font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7731;left:49><nobr>sector in developing countries provides a promising platform for</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7749;left:49><nobr>PPPs in terms of financial advantages, efficiency advantages, and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7767;left:49><nobr>innovation advantages, compared to the traditional government</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7785;left:49><nobr>procurement model (<a href=#23></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Willoughby, 2013</a></font><a href=#23></a>). Based on sophisticated</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7803;left:49><nobr>legal frameworks and rich experience, most of the risks in PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7821;left:49><nobr>projects disappear or are strongly mitigated after the construction</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7839;left:49><nobr>phase in developed countries, while some important risks</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7857;left:49><nobr>(for example, political or regulatory risks) still exist during the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7875;left:49><nobr>operation phase in developing countries (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Albornoz and Soliño,</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7893;left:49><nobr><a href=#20>2015</a><font color=#231f20>). There were evident differences in PPP project-types</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7911;left:49><nobr>between developed and developing countries, owing to differ-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7929;left:49><nobr>ences in the abilities, environments, and demands. The PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7947;left:49><nobr>project activities have been concentrated in varied project-types</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7965;left:49><nobr>in developed countries, whereas developing countries have</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7983;left:49><nobr>received only minimal infrastructural (water supply and transport,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8000;left:49><nobr>among others) investment through PPPs (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Siemiatycki, 2013</a></font>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8037;left:49><nobr><i>3.4. Publications distributed by project type</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8073;left:67><nobr>Of the 754 studies, 379 studies focused on specific infra-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8091;left:49><nobr>structure projects. As shown in <font color=#2e3192><a href=#7>Table 5</a></font><a href=#7></a>, at the top of the list,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8108;left:49><nobr>111 studies focussed the application of PPP in transport</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8126;left:49><nobr>projects. Among these studies, 64 studies applied the general-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8144;left:49><nobr>ised word ‘transport’, 32 studies conducted research on the word</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7728;left:453><nobr>‘road’, and 14 studies used the word ‘highway’. Concerning the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7749;left:453><nobr>second place on the list, 39 studies were oriented towards</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7767;left:453><nobr>the ‘health/hospital’ area, while studies including the keywords</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7785;left:453><nobr>health and hospital totalled to 25 and 14, respectively. The</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7803;left:453><nobr>results coincide with the previous research by <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Neto et al. (2016)</a></font></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7821;left:453><nobr>in which transport and health topped the list of project types.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7839;left:453><nobr>However, contrary to the findings of <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Neto et al. (2016)</a></font>, projects</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7857;left:453><nobr>oriented towards water supply, network, and power plants/</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7875;left:453><nobr>energy projects come in the top five of the list, while education</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7893;left:453><nobr>occupies the ninth position after urban rail transit and urban</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7911;left:453><nobr>development.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7929;left:470><nobr>As shown in the top five of the list in <font color=#2e3192><a href=#7>Table 5</a></font><a href=#7></a>, the history</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7947;left:453><nobr>of PPP application in transport, water, and energy projects</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7965;left:453><nobr>dates back longer than the health and network projects. In</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:7983;left:453><nobr>other words, economic infrastructure projects, which refer to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8000;left:453><nobr>facilities and services that facilitate the achievement of economic</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8018;left:453><nobr>development targets (e.g. roads, tunnels, and bridges), are</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8036;left:453><nobr>considered more mature in the PPP experience than social</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8054;left:453><nobr>infrastructure projects, which refer to facilities and services</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8072;left:453><nobr>that facilitate the achievement of social targets (e.g. hospitals,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8090;left:453><nobr>schools, and network) (<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Jefferies and McGeorge, 2009</a></font>). Based on</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8108;left:453><nobr>the clear charge mechanism, mature regulatory system, and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8126;left:453><nobr>appropriate return and risk allocation methods in economic</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8144;left:453><nobr>infrastructure projects, the scope of PPP application becomes</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8162;left:453><nobr>more extensive in transport, water, and energy PPP projects. In</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8180;left:453><nobr>the transport projects, the private finance application scope</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8198;left:453><nobr>extended from single a toll road to encompass high speed road</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8216;left:453><nobr>project, and subsequently the metropolitan transport system</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8234;left:453><nobr>(<a href=#23></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Yuan et al., 2010</a></font>). Concerning the energy domain, the PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8252;left:453><nobr>concept was first implemented for power plant projects, followed</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8269;left:453><nobr>by waste-to-energy, bioenergy, and other energy projects. Owing</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8287;left:453><nobr>to the complexities of social infrastructure projects, where clients</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8305;left:453><nobr>and building users are diversified, PPP becomes the most</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8323;left:453><nobr>challenging and interdisciplinary approaches in all procurement</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8341;left:453><nobr>methods (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Sastoque et al., 2016</a></font><a href=#22></a>). To meet the increasing needs of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8359;left:453><nobr>healthcare and signal communication, many governments make</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8377;left:453><nobr>use of private finance contracts to deliver healthcare infrastruc-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8395;left:453><nobr>ture and technical infrastructures. Health and network projects</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8413;left:453><nobr>occupy the top five positions in the list because of the huge</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8431;left:453><nobr>market demand and user-charge mechanism (<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Leviäkangas et al.,</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8449;left:453><nobr><a href=#21>2015</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#21></a>; </font><a href=#20>Colla et al., 2015</a><font color=#231f20>). Concerning PPP application, economic</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8467;left:453><nobr>infrastructure got an earlier beginning than social infrastructure;</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8485;left:453><nobr>user-charge projects witnessed a rapid development than other</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8503;left:453><nobr>projects.</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>

<div style=position:absolute;top:8539;left:58><nobr>Please cite this article as: C. Cui, et al., 2018. Review of studies on the public–private partnerships (PPP) for infrastructure projects, Int. J. Proj. Manag. <font color=#2e3192><a href=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=vi&amp;prev=_t&amp;sl=auto&amp;tl=vi&amp;u=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004>https://doi.org/</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8553;left:58><nobr><a href=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=vi&amp;prev=_t&amp;sl=auto&amp;tl=vi&amp;u=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004>10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004</a></nobr></div>
</span></font>

<div style=position:absolute;top:8576;left:0><hr><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td bgcolor=eeeeee align=right><font face=arial,sans-serif><a name=8><b>Page 8</b></a></font></td></tr></table></div><font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8689;left:82><nobr>There are three types of PPP infrastructure projects based</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8707;left:64><nobr>on payment mechanism, namely, user-charge, government</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8725;left:64><nobr>charge, and a viability gap funding. Concerning the develop-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8743;left:64><nobr>ment of user-charge infrastructure projects, the utilisation of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8760;left:64><nobr>BOT, TOT, BOOT, and ROT types of mechanisms has triggered</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8778;left:64><nobr>many initiatives such as transport, network, and water supply.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8796;left:64><nobr>In this type of infrastructure, ‘operate’ is the key characteristic</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8814;left:64><nobr>because of the nature of profitability in user-charge projects.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8832;left:64><nobr>Viability gap subsidies are necessary; however, it is difficult for</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8850;left:64><nobr>the user-charge to meet the cost recovery target and reasonable</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8868;left:64><nobr>returns of private sector or special purpose vehicles (SPV) such as</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8886;left:64><nobr>waste-to-energy and wastewater treatment (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Song et al., 2015</a></font><a href=#22></a>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8904;left:64><nobr>Therefore, the utilisations of BOT, TOT, BOOT, and ROT are</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8922;left:64><nobr>very popular in viability gap funding projects, with government’s</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8940;left:64><nobr>subsidy based on project performance. Proper capital contribu-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8958;left:64><nobr>tion proportion and joint venture model are critical factors that</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8976;left:64><nobr>contribute towards the success of these projects; for example, the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8994;left:64><nobr>Beijing No. 4 Metro line project involves private financing of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9011;left:64><nobr>rolling stock, while the public sector finances an infrastructure</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9029;left:64><nobr>building project and transfers the ownership of equipment at no</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9047;left:64><nobr>additional cost after operating the system for 30 years (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Brandão</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9065;left:64><nobr><a href=#20>et al., 2012</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#20></a>). Projects that do not possess the characteristics of</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9079;left:64><nobr>‘operate’, otherwise referred to as the non-operating PPP projects</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9101;left:64><nobr>(e.g. urban road and urban renewal) have explored many possible</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9119;left:64><nobr>solutions under government payment mechanisms like BT and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9137;left:64><nobr>governments purchase public service (GPPS) (<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Morano and</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9155;left:64><nobr><a href=#21>Tajani, 2017</a><font color=#231f20>). To sum up, BOT, TOT, BOOT, and ROT,</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8689;left:467><nobr>among others, which include ‘operate’ type projects, are suitable</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8707;left:467><nobr>for user-charge projects and infrastructure projects supported by</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8725;left:467><nobr>viability gap subsidies. However, BT and GPPS, which exclude</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8743;left:467><nobr>the ‘operate’ type projects, were considered suitable government</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8760;left:467><nobr>payment infrastructure projects.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8778;left:485><nobr>In addition to the project types set out in <font color=#2e3192><a href=#7>Table 5</a></font>, research</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8796;left:467><nobr>topics also focus on large-scale infrastructure, critical infrastruc-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8814;left:467><nobr>ture, green infrastructure, and social infrastructure, indicating the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8832;left:467><nobr>increased number of studies that focus on sustainability in PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8850;left:467><nobr>and project management.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8886;left:467><nobr><i>3.5. Publications distributed by different disciplines</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8922;left:485><nobr>The reviewed studies involved a broader scope of journals</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8940;left:467><nobr>across different disciplines. Of the 754 studies, 426 studies</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8958;left:467><nobr>focussed on specific disciplines. Among these studies, 234 studies</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8976;left:467><nobr>focussed on issues about construction management, 81 studies</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:8994;left:467><nobr>focussed on public administration, 35 studies were oriented</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9012;left:467><nobr>towards urban studies, 28 studies focussed on economics.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9030;left:467><nobr>However, other studies focussed on diverse issues about other</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9048;left:467><nobr>disciplines, such as maritime affairs, sociology, and law.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9066;left:485><nobr>Researchers in different disciplines have taken different</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9084;left:467><nobr>theoretical perspectives to explore the PPP phenomena. The</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9102;left:467><nobr>main theoretical foundations and special theories for different</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9120;left:467><nobr>disciplines are shown in <font color=#2e3192><a href=#8>Fig. 3</a></font><a href=#8></a>. Based on <font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Andon’s (2012)</a></font></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9138;left:467><nobr>research agenda principle, the main theoretical foundations</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9155;left:467><nobr>were classified into nature and rationale for PPPs, merit and</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9695;left:283><nobr>Fig. 3. Theoretical foundations of PPP research in different disciplines.</nobr></div>
