<div style=position:absolute;top:9766;left:0><hr><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td bgcolor=eeeeee align=right><font face=arial,sans-serif><a name=9><b>Page 9</b></a></font></td></tr></table></div><font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9879;left:49><nobr>worth of PPPs, decisions to undertake PPPs, ex-post evalua-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9897;left:49><nobr>tions of PPPs, regulations and guidance concerning PPP, and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9915;left:49><nobr>PPP research methods. Classical theories played critical role in</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9933;left:49><nobr>all the disciplines concerning PPP practice and research such as</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9950;left:49><nobr>the complex system theory, contract theory, and organizational</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9968;left:49><nobr>theory. Among the main theoretical foundations, agent theory,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9986;left:49><nobr>game theory, stakeholder theory, incentive theory, and contract</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10004;left:49><nobr>theory were most widely used by former researchers. Accord-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10022;left:49><nobr>ing to the principal-agent theory, as an agent, the private sector</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10040;left:49><nobr>can maximum advantages on technology and management</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10058;left:49><nobr>in PPP projects, based on principal sector’s incentive. The</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10076;left:49><nobr>Nash bargaining game theory provides the theoretical basis for</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10094;left:49><nobr>awarding contract among the public sector, private sector, and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10112;left:49><nobr>other stakeholders.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10130;left:67><nobr>Different theoretical perspectives in different disciplines</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10148;left:49><nobr>are provided in special theories (<a href=#8></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#8>Fig. 3</a></font><a href=#8></a>). Compared to other</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10166;left:49><nobr>disciplines, researchers in construction management paid more</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10184;left:49><nobr>attention to detailed issues in PPP implications, such as revenue</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10201;left:49><nobr>issues, property rights, and flexibility management issues.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10219;left:49><nobr>Real options were widely used in construction management to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10237;left:49><nobr>guarantee revenue under contractual right (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Chiara et al., 2007</a></font><a href=#20></a>;</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10255;left:49><nobr><a href=#21>Liu et al., 2014b</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#21></a>; </font><a href=#20>Carbonara et al., 2014</a><font color=#231f20>). Real options were also</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10273;left:49><nobr>used to value the financial incentives offered by government</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10291;left:49><nobr>(<font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Alonso-Conde et al., 2007</a></font><a href=#20></a>), provide flexibilities for PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10309;left:49><nobr>contracts by capturing the value of renegotiation (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Xiong and</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10327;left:49><nobr><a href=#23>Zhang, 2016</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#23></a>), and identify an effective interval of concession</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10345;left:49><nobr>period (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Lv et al., 2015</a></font>). The government regulation theory was</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10363;left:49><nobr>used to explore a way to enhance PPP management flexibility</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10381;left:49><nobr>and financial feasibility, thereby ensuring the delivery of public</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10399;left:49><nobr>services and ensuring the success of PPP projects (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Mouraviev</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10417;left:49><nobr><a href=#22>and Kakabadse, 2015</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#22></a>; </font><a href=#23>Zhang et al., 2016</a><font color=#231f20>). Concerning certain</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10435;left:49><nobr>phases of an infrastructure construction project (e.g. design,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10453;left:49><nobr>construction, operations, and maintenance), property rights</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10470;left:49><nobr>theory was used to provide a solution to the long existing</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10488;left:49><nobr>property right paradox and to estimate the suitability of PPPs for</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10506;left:49><nobr>facilities (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Rouhani and Niemeier, 2014</a></font><a href=#22></a>; <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Teo and Bridge, 2016</a></font>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10524;left:49><nobr>The capital budgeting theory focused on the calculation of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10542;left:49><nobr>cost and revenue, which are the key elements involved in the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10560;left:49><nobr>evaluation of the value and effect of PPP projects (<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Jun, 2010</a></font><a href=#21></a>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10578;left:67><nobr>Researchers in the public administration area paid more</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10596;left:49><nobr>attention to social issues. The social exchange theory was used</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9879;left:453><nobr>to explore informal contracts to enhance cooperation effects</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9897;left:453><nobr>between public sector and private sector over a long period of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9915;left:453><nobr>time. Assuming PPP projects and external environment as a</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9933;left:453><nobr>social system, the social ecology theory was used to explore</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9950;left:453><nobr>relationships among the elements in this social system including</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9968;left:453><nobr>public sector, private sector, other stakeholders, and external</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:9986;left:453><nobr>environment (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Zhang and Jia, 2010</a></font><a href=#23></a>). Public administration</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10004;left:453><nobr>researches focussed on the social environment, while urban</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10022;left:453><nobr>studies focussed on the natural environment. The resource</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10040;left:453><nobr>dependence theory was used to explore a sustainable urban</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10058;left:453><nobr>development method for improving the local resources use,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10076;left:453><nobr>living standards, and sustainable development, especially of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10094;left:453><nobr>urban areas (<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Kyvelou and Karaiskou, 2006</a></font><a href=#21></a>). Ecological</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10112;left:453><nobr>problems have also attracted researchers to focus on the urban</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10130;left:453><nobr>development area. The ecological economy theory was used to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10148;left:453><nobr>explore the new production and consumption patterns to achieve</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10166;left:453><nobr>an economically developed and a highly ecological city system</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10184;left:453><nobr>(<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Li et al., 2016a</a></font><a href=#21></a>). In the field of economics, researchers used the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10201;left:453><nobr>new institutional economics theory to explore game and trust</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10219;left:453><nobr>relationship between public and private sectors and found that</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10237;left:453><nobr>the common role of a national PPP unit contributes towards</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10255;left:453><nobr>creating trust between the public and private sectors (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Tserng et</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10273;left:453><nobr><a href=#22>al., 2011</a><font color=#231f20>). The new institutional economics theory was also used</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10291;left:453><nobr>to develop and expand a set of new institutional capacities</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10309;left:453><nobr>designed for the implementation of amended (and changing)</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10327;left:453><nobr>government responsibilities in PPP projects (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Mouraviev and</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10345;left:453><nobr><a href=#21>Kakabadse, 2014a</a><font color=#231f20>). The arbitrage pricing theory was used to</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10363;left:453><nobr>understand the equilibrium relationship between risk and return</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10381;left:453><nobr>in economic perspective for PPP projects.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10417;left:453><nobr><b>4. Classification of research topics</b></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10453;left:470><nobr>NVivo is utilised to explore the possible classification of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10471;left:453><nobr>research topics in PPP studies. First, information including</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10488;left:453><nobr>title, keywords, and abstract (full text if there is no abstract) is</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10506;left:453><nobr>imported in Nvivo. Second, word cloud analyses were</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10524;left:453><nobr>conducted based on the word frequency analysis, as shown in</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10542;left:453><nobr><a href=#9>Fig. 4</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#9></a>. The word frequency analysis is a data exploration</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10560;left:453><nobr>technique that can classify research topics by analysing the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10578;left:453><nobr>scientific content indicated by high-frequency words. Third, the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10596;left:453><nobr>horizontal dendrogram is generated based on cluster analysis.</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:10884;left:358><nobr>Fig. 4. Word cloud for all groups.</nobr></div>

<div style=position:absolute;top:10956;left:0><hr><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td bgcolor=eeeeee align=right><font face=arial,sans-serif><a name=10><b>Page 10</b></a></font></td></tr></table></div><font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11069;left:64><nobr>In the horizontal dendrogram, the cluster analysis demonstrates</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11087;left:64><nobr>that similar words were clustered together on the same branch</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11105;left:64><nobr>and different items were clustered further apart. Subsequently,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11123;left:64><nobr>a clustering analysis of words that are used in abstracts and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11140;left:64><nobr>keywords is conducted to ensure that the classifications of the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11158;left:64><nobr>research topics are reasonable. A correlation cluster analysis,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11176;left:64><nobr>which selects word correlation based on the clustering, is</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11194;left:64><nobr>performed to find statistical relationships between these words.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11212;left:64><nobr>In the current research, the cluster analysis was performed with</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11230;left:64><nobr>a selection of grouped items from a more specific internal</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11248;left:64><nobr>material, establishing the existence of correlation measurement</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11266;left:64><nobr>as the criterion (<a href=#23></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Zapata-Sepúlveda et al., 2012</a></font><a href=#23></a>). Meanwhile, a</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11284;left:64><nobr>clustering algorithm guided by the Pearson correlation coeffi-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11302;left:64><nobr>cient is used to generate a dendrogram or cluster tree.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11320;left:64><nobr>Subsequently, the research topics were classified into six</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11338;left:64><nobr>categories (see <font color=#2e3192><a href=#10>Fig. 5</a></font><a href=#10></a>). The function words were not</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11356;left:64><nobr>considered; the clustered high frequency words were consid-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11374;left:64><nobr>ered useful for categorizing topic groups. The sources of words,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11391;left:64><nobr>namely, articles including a typical word in the title, abstract,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11409;left:64><nobr>and keywords were used to summarise the research topics in</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11427;left:64><nobr>each group as an auxiliary instrument.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11069;left:485><nobr>In the study by <font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Ke et al. (2009)</a></font><a href=#21></a>, seven groups, namely,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11087;left:467><nobr>investment environment, procurement, economic viability,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11105;left:467><nobr>financial package, risk management, governance issue, and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11123;left:467><nobr>integration research were explored and summarised. However,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11140;left:467><nobr>the results of the current study clearly indicated that new topics</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11158;left:467><nobr>and relationships between topics have been introduced. First,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11176;left:467><nobr>performance management, which includes key performance</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11194;left:467><nobr>indicators (KPI) and performance measurement, were studied</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11212;left:467><nobr>to drive PPP projects efficiently. Second, Value for Money</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11230;left:467><nobr>(VFM) was investigated by many researchers. Third, there exist</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11248;left:467><nobr>relationships between different research topics. By considering</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11266;left:467><nobr>the results of the word cluster and <font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Ke et al.’s (2009) </a></font>and</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11284;left:467><nobr><a href=#22>Themistocleous and Wearne’s (2000) </a><font color=#231f20>categorisation of research</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11302;left:467><nobr>topics, six potential research topics were proposed—financial</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11320;left:467><nobr>package and PPP application (G1), economics viability and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11338;left:467><nobr>VFM (G2), risk management and success factor (G3), procure-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11356;left:467><nobr>ment and contract management (G4), performance management</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11374;left:467><nobr>(G5), and governance and regulation (G6). The aim was to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11391;left:467><nobr>identify topics in this broad research area, instead of classifying</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11409;left:467><nobr>the existing literature. The inclusion of the same article is</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11427;left:467><nobr>permitted in different statistical groups, and simultaneously the</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12075;left:327><nobr>Fig. 5. The horizontal dendrogram of the six groups.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11028;left:838><nobr>9</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:11028;left:264><nobr><i>C. Cui et al. / International Journal of Project Management xx (2018) xxx</i>–<i>xxx</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12109;left:73><nobr>Please cite this article as: C. Cui, et al., 2018. Review of studies on the public–private partnerships (PPP) for infrastructure projects, Int. J. Proj. Manag. <font color=#2e3192><a href=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=vi&amp;prev=_t&amp;sl=auto&amp;tl=vi&amp;u=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004>https://doi.org/</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12123;left:73><nobr><a href=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=vi&amp;prev=_t&amp;sl=auto&amp;tl=vi&amp;u=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004>10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004</a></nobr></div>

<div style=position:absolute;top:12146;left:0><hr><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td bgcolor=eeeeee align=right><font face=arial,sans-serif><a name=11><b>Page 11</b></a></font></td></tr></table></div><font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12528;left:49><nobr>cumulative coverage of every word in each group against the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12546;left:49><nobr>material source is shown in <font color=#2e3192><a href=#11>Fig. 6</a></font>.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12582;left:49><nobr><b>5. Discussion of research topics</b></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12617;left:49><nobr><i>5.1. Group 1: financial package and PPP application (G1)</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12653;left:67><nobr>This topic focuses on financial package and uses PPP to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12671;left:49><nobr>deliver infrastructure projects efficiently. Financial package and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12689;left:49><nobr>PPP application are the most fundamental topics in PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12707;left:49><nobr>research, although they have a low material source coverage</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12725;left:49><nobr>of 5.8%. The research history of these topics clearly shows a</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12743;left:49><nobr>notable change of research content from ‘how to operate PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12761;left:49><nobr>projects’ to ‘how to popularise the utilization of PPP’.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12779;left:67><nobr>At the beginning of the 1990s, researchers attempted to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12797;left:49><nobr>establish the features of PPP projects by summarising the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12815;left:49><nobr>processes of actual PPP projects (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Tiong, 1990</a></font><a href=#22></a>) and by</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12833;left:49><nobr>analysing the cost, concession, equity structure (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Tiong,</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12850;left:49><nobr><a href=#22>1995a</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#22></a>), and contracts, thereby setting the theoretical founda-</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12868;left:49><nobr>tion for the study of PPP application and practice (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Tiong,</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12886;left:49><nobr><a href=#22>1992</a><font color=#231f20>). They analysed the relationship between the investors'</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12904;left:49><nobr>return on equity, projects' net present value, and debt</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12922;left:49><nobr>capacity, and revealed that debt capacity has a direct impact</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12940;left:49><nobr>on the projects’ value to investors. At that time, the aim of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12958;left:49><nobr>most of the studies in this area was to clarify the difference</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12976;left:49><nobr>between PPP’s procurement and traditional models of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12994;left:49><nobr>procurement and to demonstrate the practical operation of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13012;left:49><nobr>PPP projects.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13030;left:67><nobr>After 2000, on the one hand, related articles paid more</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13048;left:49><nobr>attention to detailed issues in the financial package. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Bakatjan</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13066;left:49><nobr><a href=#20>et al. (2003) </a><font color=#231f20>presented a simplified model, which combined a</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13084;left:49><nobr>financial model and a linear programming model, to determine</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13102;left:49><nobr>the optimum equity level for decision-makers at the evaluation</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13120;left:49><nobr>stage of a BOT project. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Smith et al. (2004) </a></font>analysed the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13137;left:49><nobr>negotiation, construction, and operational phases of the Huaibei</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13155;left:49><nobr>power plant project in China, and found that the development</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13173;left:49><nobr>of PPP markets depends on whether the PPP payment</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13191;left:49><nobr>mechanism can be managed properly as an incentive. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Iyer and</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13209;left:49><nobr><a href=#21>Sagheer (2011) </a><font color=#231f20>presented a new genetic-algorithm (GA)-based</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13227;left:49><nobr>model that yields a set of optimal solutions on capital structure</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13245;left:49><nobr>for the key decision variables—grant, debt, and equity. On the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13263;left:49><nobr>other hand, the focus of PPP research shifted towards ‘how</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12528;left:453><nobr>to popularise the utilisation of PPP in more regions and for</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12546;left:453><nobr>more types of projects’. Concerning the application of PPP,</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12564;left:453><nobr><a href=#22>Shen et al. (1996) </a><font color=#231f20>studied the widespread use of PPP in</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12581;left:453><nobr>developed countries and examined the nature of BOT, potential</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12599;left:453><nobr>investment market in China, Chinese government’s policies,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12617;left:453><nobr>and practical procedures of applying the BOT system.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12635;left:453><nobr>Subsequently, they identified the major areas where BOT</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12653;left:453><nobr>systems are applied in China (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Shen et al., 1996</a></font><a href=#22></a>). The</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12671;left:453><nobr>application of PPP in developing countries was studied by</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12689;left:453><nobr><a href=#21>Malini (1999)</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#21></a>, who developed a simulation model to examine</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12707;left:453><nobr>the financial viability affected by various options such as the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12725;left:453><nobr>toll structure, toll revision schedule, extent of municipal grant,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12743;left:453><nobr>and duration of the concession period. In addition, <font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Malini</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12761;left:453><nobr><a href=#21>(1999) </a><font color=#231f20>undertook research on the application of PPP in bridge</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12779;left:453><nobr>construction projects. Subsequently, the research on PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12797;left:453><nobr>application extended to urban land development projects</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12815;left:453><nobr>(<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Glumac et al., 2015</a></font><a href=#20></a>; <font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Leland and Read, 2013</a></font><a href=#21></a>), power plant</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12833;left:453><nobr>projects (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Smith et al., 2004</a></font>; <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Wang and Tiong, 2000</a></font><a href=#22></a>), rail</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12850;left:453><nobr>projects (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Chang and Chen, 2001</a></font><a href=#20></a>; <font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Cohen and Kamga, 2013</a></font><a href=#20></a>),</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12868;left:453><nobr>waste collection and recycling (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Ahmed and Ali, 2004</a></font>;</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12886;left:453><nobr><a href=#20>Bhuiyan, 2010</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#20></a>), and tunnel projects (</font><a href=#23>Yu et al., 2014</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#23></a>; </font><a href=#23>Zhang</a></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12904;left:453><nobr><a href=#23>et al., 2002</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#23></a>), among others. Recently, the use of PPP extended to</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12922;left:453><nobr>include the procurement of social infrastructure projects, such as</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12940;left:453><nobr>airports (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Doll and Karagyozov, 2010</a></font><a href=#20></a>; <font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Jain, 2015</a></font><a href=#21></a>), schools (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Amjad</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12958;left:453><nobr><a href=#20>and MacLeod, 2014</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#20></a>; </font><a href=#21>Kumari, 2016</a><font color=#231f20>), hospitals (<a href=#20></a></font><a href=#20>De Marco et al.,</a></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12976;left:453><nobr><a href=#20>2012</a><font color=#231f20>; </font><a href=#21>Li et al., 2014</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#21></a>) and prisons (</font><a href=#21>Jefferies and McGeorge, 2009</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#21></a>).</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12994;left:470><nobr>Both in economic and social infrastructure, sustainability is</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13012;left:453><nobr>becoming increasingly important in the delivery of infrastruc-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13030;left:453><nobr>ture projects because stakeholders require both ethicality and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13048;left:453><nobr>economic efficiency during a project's life cycle (<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Kivilä et al.,</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13066;left:453><nobr><a href=#21>2017</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#21></a>). As the main goal, among the 17 Sustainable Develop-</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13084;left:453><nobr>ment Goals (SDGs) of the United Nations (UN), building</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13102;left:453><nobr>quality, reliable, sustainable, and resilient infrastructure is</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13119;left:453><nobr>crucial to achieving sustainable development in many countries.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13137;left:453><nobr>It is proven that PPPs promote the development of personal</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13155;left:453><nobr>competences and support project management for sustainable</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13173;left:453><nobr>infrastructure development (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Ríos et al., 2016</a></font>). Additionally, PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13191;left:453><nobr>is now implemented by the UN as an important tool to achieve</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13209;left:453><nobr>the 17 SDGs. The research trends in this topic may enable</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13227;left:453><nobr>practitioners to emphasise detailed issues in PPP application,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13245;left:453><nobr>study how to apply the PPP model in other types of infrastructure</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13263;left:453><nobr>projects within larger geographical areas effectively and</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12479;left:303><nobr>Fig. 6. Material source coverage statistics of each group.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12218;left:49><nobr>10</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:12218;left:250><nobr><i>C. Cui et al. / International Journal of Project Management xx (2018) xxx</i>–<i>xxx</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13299;left:58><nobr>Please cite this article as: C. Cui, et al., 2018. Review of studies on the public–private partnerships (PPP) for infrastructure projects, Int. J. Proj. Manag. <font color=#2e3192><a href=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=vi&amp;prev=_t&amp;sl=auto&amp;tl=vi&amp;u=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004>https://doi.org/</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>

<div style=position:absolute;top:13336;left:0><hr><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td bgcolor=eeeeee align=right><font face=arial,sans-serif><a name=12><b>Page 12</b></a></font></td></tr></table></div><font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13449;left:64><nobr>efficiently, and research on how to operate PPPs to achieve the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13467;left:64><nobr>SDGs of UN.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13503;left:64><nobr><i>5.2. Group 2: economic viability and VFM (G2)</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13538;left:82><nobr>This topic focuses on how to evaluate the economic viability</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13556;left:64><nobr>of PPP and decide whether PPP is suitable for use on specific</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13574;left:64><nobr>infrastructure projects. Based on the research conducted by <font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Hurst</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13592;left:64><nobr><a href=#21>and Reeves (2004)</a><font color=#231f20>, which adopts the criteria of competition,</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13610;left:64><nobr>efficiency/VFM, and re-financing to examine specific PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13628;left:64><nobr>projects, this topic includes economic feasibility, VFM, stake-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13646;left:64><nobr>holders' satisfaction, and the economic environment.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13664;left:82><nobr>Research about PPP's economic feasibility assessment has</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13682;left:64><nobr>been undertaken by <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Wamuziri and Clearie (2005) </a></font>who provide</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13700;left:64><nobr>critical techniques and tools for cost-benefit analysis through</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13718;left:64><nobr>their assessment of the economic feasibility of the second Forth</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13736;left:64><nobr>Road Bridge in Scotland. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Lee (2011) </a></font>designed an options-based</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13754;left:64><nobr>economic analysis with the simulation of multiple scenarios,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13771;left:64><nobr>namely, ‘adaptive investment strategies’ (i.e. ‘start robust, then</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13789;left:64><nobr>adapt’), based on the performance of inter-agency and public-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13807;left:64><nobr>private collaboration in earlier stages. Over the past few years,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13825;left:64><nobr>the focus of studies about a PPP's economic feasibility has</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13843;left:64><nobr>shifted from the calculation of evaluation indices of traditional</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13861;left:64><nobr>methods of economic feasibility assessment to the improvement</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13879;left:64><nobr>of evaluation methods as well as the establishment of brand new</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13897;left:64><nobr>evaluation systems.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13915;left:82><nobr>A similar approach is observed concerning the topic of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13933;left:64><nobr>decision-making-based economic feasibility. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Fantozzi et al.</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13951;left:64><nobr><a href=#20>(2014) </a><font color=#231f20>examined the practice of developing public sector</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13969;left:64><nobr>comparator (PSC) models and analysed the PPP VFM when</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13987;left:64><nobr>it was applied to the assessment of the economic feasibility of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14005;left:64><nobr>bioenergy projects. VFM is often regarded as the monetary</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14023;left:64><nobr>value of the capital through PPP adoption instead of a more</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14040;left:64><nobr>traditional procurement option. Assuming all factors are equal</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14058;left:64><nobr>(i.e. quality and outcomes), VFM is demonstrated when the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14076;left:64><nobr>total present value cost (PPP value) of private sector supply is</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14094;left:64><nobr>less than the net present value of the base cost of the service</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14112;left:64><nobr>(PSC value), adjusted for the cost of risks to be retained by the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14130;left:64><nobr>government, cost adjustments for transferable risk and compet-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14148;left:64><nobr>itive neutrality effects (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Grimsey and Lewis, 2005</a></font>). Studies</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14166;left:64><nobr>about VFM remain prevalent throughout the extant literature</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14184;left:64><nobr>and continue to be a key area of focus for researchers. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Heald</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14202;left:64><nobr><a href=#20>(2003) </a><font color=#231f20>analysed VFM from a theoretical perspective of </font><a href=#22>Pitt</a></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14220;left:64><nobr><a href=#22>et al. (2006) </a><font color=#231f20>and explored the principle factors increasing VFM;</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14238;left:64><nobr>the principle factors included optimal allocation and valuation of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14256;left:64><nobr>risk, output-based specification, competition, contract duration</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14274;left:64><nobr>and scope, bid costs, innovation, borrowing costs, private sector</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14292;left:64><nobr>management skills, client management skills, performance</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14310;left:64><nobr>measurement and incentives, and contract flexibility. Among</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14327;left:64><nobr>these factors, the valuation of risk, borrowing costs, and bid costs</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14345;left:64><nobr>were established as the key parameters of the PSC value. The</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14363;left:64><nobr>above-mentioned research focussed on the effect of VFM on</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14381;left:64><nobr>decision-making and how to count VFM in practice. However,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14399;left:64><nobr>VFM analysis has failed to reflect the long-term social impact</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14417;left:64><nobr>of infrastructure development. To achieve sustainability goals,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14435;left:64><nobr>social parameters must be considered for extending VFM</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14453;left:64><nobr>assessment (<a href=#19></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#19>Agarchand and Laishram, 2017</a></font>). Extending the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13449;left:467><nobr>VFM assessment of PPP might significantly enhance the VFM</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13467;left:467><nobr>conceptualization by more comprehensive, and accurate assess-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13485;left:467><nobr>ment of economic and social value that PPPs create (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Mouraviev</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13503;left:467><nobr><a href=#22>and Kakabadse, 2014b</a><font color=#231f20>). Social value, which refers to the benefit</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13520;left:467><nobr>that a society gains as a whole from a PPP infrastructure project,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13538;left:467><nobr>is considered a key sustainability indicator and includes equality,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13556;left:467><nobr>public meeting, and human rights (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Hueskes et al., 2017</a></font>). With</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13574;left:467><nobr>the widespread application of VFM assessment and a lack of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13592;left:467><nobr>attention towards social value in VFM analysis, the focus of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13610;left:467><nobr>academic research concerning VFM is adjusted to explore how to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13628;left:467><nobr>improve (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Visconti et al., 2014</a></font><a href=#22></a>), enhance (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Berawi et al., 2014</a></font>),</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13646;left:467><nobr>and maximise VFM (<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Martins et al., 2014</a></font><a href=#21></a>); what factors drive</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13664;left:467><nobr>(<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Ismail, 2013</a></font>; <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Nisar, 2007</a></font><a href=#22></a>) and influence VFM in general (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Hu</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13682;left:467><nobr><a href=#21>et al., 2014</a><font color=#231f20>); and how to appraise social value in VFM assessment</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13700;left:467><nobr>(<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Boardman and Hellowell, 2016</a></font>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13718;left:485><nobr>The key to an effective PPP lies in the partnership between</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13736;left:467><nobr>the public and private sectors as well as in the relationship</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13754;left:467><nobr>among other project stakeholders. As a pioneer, <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Sohail et al.</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13771;left:467><nobr><a href=#22>(2004) </a><font color=#231f20>used both quantitative and qualitative approaches to</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13789;left:467><nobr>extract the perspectives of users, operators, and regulators of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13807;left:467><nobr>transport projects. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Henjewele et al. (2013) </a></font>analysed the process of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13825;left:467><nobr>stakeholder consultation and management; this process involved</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13843;left:467><nobr>placing the public at the centre of planning, construction, and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13861;left:467><nobr>operation of PPP projects that aim to achieve mutual benefits. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>De</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13879;left:467><nobr><a href=#20>Schepper et al. (2014) </a><font color=#231f20>analysed the management responsibilities</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13897;left:467><nobr>among critical stakeholders and found that meaningful division</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13915;left:467><nobr>of responsibilities will affect the requirements of stakeholders</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13933;left:467><nobr>in an active or passive way. To achieve stakeholder satisfaction</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13951;left:467><nobr>from a financial perspective, the most important expectations of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13969;left:467><nobr>relevant stakeholders were identified across five different stages</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13987;left:467><nobr>in the projects by <font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Kurniawan et al. (2014)</a></font>. These stages included</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14005;left:467><nobr>the assessment of a project's ability to carry senior debt,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14023;left:467><nobr>sensitivity analysis for key commercial issues, debt service</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14040;left:467><nobr>evaluation towards cost overrun and other adverse events, and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14058;left:467><nobr>assurance of a secure operational cash flow. On the one hand, the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14076;left:467><nobr>degree of stakeholder satisfaction influences the suitability of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14094;left:467><nobr>a project for PPP; on the other hand, stakeholder collaboration</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14112;left:467><nobr>and performance influence the application conditions of PPP.</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14130;left:467><nobr><a href=#21>Mladenovic et al. (2013) </a><font color=#231f20>introduced an approach to assess</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14148;left:467><nobr>the success or failure of PPP projects from the standpoint of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14166;left:467><nobr>each stakeholder and fulfil the different objectives of specific</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14184;left:467><nobr>stakeholder groups through a weighted combination.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14202;left:485><nobr>Economic feasibility, value for money, and stakeholder</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14220;left:467><nobr>satisfaction are internal factors that contribute towards assessing</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14238;left:467><nobr>the appropriateness of PPP projects, while the economic envi-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14256;left:467><nobr>ronment is an important external condition. Therefore, several</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14274;left:467><nobr>studies focus on how PPP projects respond to the economic</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14292;left:467><nobr>environment (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Daito et al., 2013</a></font><a href=#20></a>; <font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Galilea and Medda, 2010</a></font>) and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14309;left:467><nobr>economic development (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Fitch et al., 2015</a></font>; <font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Zangoueinezhad and</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14327;left:467><nobr><a href=#23>Azar, 2014</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#23></a>). In summary, the assessment of the appropriateness</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14345;left:467><nobr>and the optimisation of PPP application conditions are important</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14363;left:467><nobr>elements of the decision-making process for PPP projects.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14399;left:467><nobr><i>5.3. Group 3: risk management and success factors (G3)</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14435;left:485><nobr>As showed in <font color=#2e3192><a href=#10>Fig. 5</a></font>, clustered result of words in Group 3</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14453;left:467><nobr>illustrated a close correlation between risk management and</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13408;left:832><nobr>11</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:13408;left:264><nobr><i>C. Cui et al. / International Journal of Project Management xx (2018) xxx</i>–<i>xxx</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14489;left:73><nobr>Please cite this article as: C. Cui, et al., 2018. Review of studies on the public–private partnerships (PPP) for infrastructure projects, Int. J. Proj. Manag. <font color=#2e3192><a href=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=vi&amp;prev=_t&amp;sl=auto&amp;tl=vi&amp;u=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004>https://doi.org/</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14503;left:73><nobr><a href=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=vi&amp;prev=_t&amp;sl=auto&amp;tl=vi&amp;u=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004>10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004</a></nobr></div>
</span></font>

<div style=position:absolute;top:14526;left:0><hr><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td bgcolor=eeeeee align=right><font face=arial,sans-serif><a name=13><b>Page 13</b></a></font></td></tr></table></div><font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14639;left:49><nobr>success factor. Therefore, this topic colligates PPP risk manage-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14657;left:49><nobr>ment and success factors and focuses on exploring methods for</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14675;left:49><nobr>risk identification, risk evaluation, and risk allocation; it also</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14693;left:49><nobr>explores methods for identifying success factors.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14710;left:67><nobr>Throughout the literature it is clear that successful PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14728;left:49><nobr>projects exhibited unique strategies and capabilities in risk</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14746;left:49><nobr>management (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Tiong, 1995b</a></font>); however, risk evaluation is so</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14764;left:49><nobr>complex that it requires an analysis of risk from different</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14782;left:49><nobr>perspectives of public and private entities (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Grimsey and Lewis,</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14800;left:49><nobr><a href=#20>2002</a><font color=#231f20>). </font><a href=#22>Shen and Wu (2005) </a><font color=#231f20>explore the way in which various</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14818;left:49><nobr>risks existing in the BOT project implementation process have</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14836;left:49><nobr>an impact on project cash flow, including revenue and cost. The</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14854;left:49><nobr>first step to estimate the influence of risk involves the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14872;left:49><nobr>identification of risk that is specific to each project. The key</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14890;left:49><nobr>risks common to many PPP projects that impact revenue are traffic</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14908;left:49><nobr>revenue risk, operation risk, demand risk, and debt servicing risk</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14926;left:49><nobr>(<font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Singh and Kalidindi, 2006</a></font>), while those impacting cost include</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14944;left:49><nobr>financing, construction, and operation cost overruns (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Ibrahim et</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14961;left:49><nobr><a href=#21>al., 2006</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#21></a>). The perceived magnitude of each risk and the</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14979;left:49><nobr>interrelationships of risks in PPP projects enable decision-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14997;left:49><nobr>makers to take appropriate steps in prioritising and analysing</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15015;left:49><nobr>project process (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Iyer and Sagheer, 2010</a></font><a href=#21></a>). Based on identifying and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15033;left:49><nobr>allocating the main risks embedded in the project during the initial</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15051;left:49><nobr>stages of the project (planning and design), the decision-makers</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15069;left:49><nobr>easily find a cost-effective way to control risk and maximise</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15087;left:49><nobr>investment value optimally (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Pellegrino et al., 2013</a></font>). Strategies</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15105;left:49><nobr>adopted by project managers usually depend on the predictability</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15123;left:49><nobr>of risk impact and controllability of the risk outcome</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15141;left:49><nobr>(<font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Trangkanont and Charoenngam, 2014</a></font>). The decision-making</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15159;left:49><nobr>process becomes more systematic and practical when the risk</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15177;left:49><nobr>management capabilities of project managers are correctly</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15195;left:49><nobr>evaluated (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Ameyaw and Chan, 2015</a></font>). Concerning the methods</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15213;left:49><nobr>of risk evaluation, the most widely used technique is the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15230;left:49><nobr>application of a risk register matrix, which includes the specific</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15248;left:49><nobr>impact and probability of occurrence of each identified risk. This</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15266;left:49><nobr>may be considered alongside a two-dimensional value curve</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15284;left:49><nobr>including performance versus worth (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Tarek et al., 2002</a></font>). Another</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15302;left:49><nobr>more recent technique is a fuzzy synthetic evaluation approach,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15320;left:49><nobr>which is becoming increasingly popular as a means of assessing</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15338;left:49><nobr>the risk level (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Ameyaw and Chan, 2013</a></font>; <font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Xu et al., 2010</a></font>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15356;left:49><nobr>Moreover, the Monte Carlo method is used as an effective tool for</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15374;left:49><nobr>simulating indeterminacy during the construction and concession</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15392;left:49><nobr>periods (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Alonso-Conde et al., 2007</a></font><a href=#20></a>; <font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Chang and Ko, 2016</a></font><a href=#20></a>;</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15410;left:49><nobr><a href=#23>Wibowo and Alfen, 2013</a><font color=#231f20>).</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15428;left:67><nobr>As one of the main benefits of the PPP models, the allocation</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15446;left:49><nobr>of risk between public and private sectors has attracted significant</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15464;left:49><nobr>interest from researchers. The fundamental concept of proper risk</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15482;left:49><nobr>allocation to enable both public and private sectors to adopt the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15499;left:49><nobr>most appropriate strategy of risk allocation was confirmed by</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15517;left:49><nobr><a href=#19>Abednego and Ogunlana (2006)</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#19></a>. Risk allocation strategies were</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15535;left:49><nobr>further studied, particularly, in terms of governance structure</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15553;left:49><nobr>(<font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Jin and Zhang, 2011</a></font><a href=#21></a>; <font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Jin and Doloi, 2008</a></font>). Due to differences in</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15571;left:49><nobr>PPP collaboration and policy background, the way in which risk</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15589;left:49><nobr>allocation is carried out varies by regions; this is resulting in a</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15607;left:49><nobr>series of risk allocation models for different regions (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Chung et al.,</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15625;left:49><nobr><a href=#20>2010</a><font color=#231f20>; </font><a href=#20>Ameyaw and Chan, 2013</a><font color=#231f20>; </font><a href=#22>Sastoque et al., 2016</a><font color=#231f20>; </font><a href=#23>Xu et al.,</a></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15643;left:49><nobr><a href=#23>2010</a><font color=#231f20>). Concerning the vital function of risk allocation, the</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14639;left:453><nobr>optimal allocation of risk is considered as one of the principle</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14657;left:453><nobr>factors in evaluating and creating VFM. Properly assessing risks</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14675;left:453><nobr>to determine whether the public agency can transfer to the private</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14693;left:453><nobr>sector is the most critical step in the VFM evaluation (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Ameyaw</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14710;left:453><nobr><a href=#20>et al., 2015</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#20></a>). Concerning the research method, empirical research</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14728;left:453><nobr>on risk allocation employs techniques such as literature analysis,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14746;left:453><nobr>survey tools, results analysis, modelling, and case studies to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14764;left:453><nobr>explore the topic across the range of project types.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14782;left:470><nobr>In the past decade, a new approach named ‘real options’</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14800;left:453><nobr>became gradually popular in this field. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Alonso-Conde et al.</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14818;left:453><nobr><a href=#20>(2007) </a><font color=#231f20>showed through case studies how PPP-imposed conditions</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14836;left:453><nobr>can be treated as real options, how these options affect the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14854;left:453><nobr>incentive to invest, and how the public sector can transfer</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14872;left:453><nobr>considerable value to the private sector through government</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14890;left:453><nobr>guarantees. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Park et al. (2013) </a></font>presented a real option-based</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14908;left:453><nobr>contract model to guarantee appropriate risk-sharing between</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14926;left:453><nobr>private entities and governments. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Pellegrino et al. (2013)</a></font></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14944;left:453><nobr>developed an option-based risk management framework that</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14961;left:453><nobr>can be related to risk mitigation strategies. Therefore, the real</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14979;left:453><nobr>options method is considered more flexible than the prevalent</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14997;left:453><nobr>approaches and it represents an important step towards improving</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15015;left:453><nobr>understanding of risk mitigation in PPP projects.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15033;left:470><nobr>It is clear from the analysis of previous research that risk</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15051;left:453><nobr>evaluation and risk allocation, as critical issues for PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15069;left:453><nobr>projects, will continue to be key research topics in the future.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15087;left:453><nobr>To improve the efficiency of risk management, researchers plan</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15105;left:453><nobr>to evaluate risk in a more accurate way and explore new</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15123;left:453><nobr>approaches of risk-sharing among stakeholders of PPP projects.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15141;left:453><nobr>Owing to the fact that poor risk management practices reduce</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15159;left:453><nobr>the chance of success within PPP projects, <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Tiong (1992)</a></font></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15177;left:453><nobr>identifies the importance of the calculated risk-taker as the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15195;left:453><nobr>critical success factor of PPP projects. Subsequently, the topic</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15213;left:453><nobr>of critical success factors (CSFs) has become popular among</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15230;left:453><nobr>PPP researchers. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Osei-Kyei and Chan (2015) </a></font>summarised the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15248;left:453><nobr>findings of the PPP CSFs studies from 1990 to 2013 as well as</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15266;left:453><nobr>the CSFs of the reviewed PPP projects. The CSFs that have</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15284;left:453><nobr>become widely accepted by scholars include appropriate risk</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15302;left:453><nobr>allocation and sharing, strong private consortia, political support,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15320;left:453><nobr>public/community support, transparent procurement, favourable</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15338;left:453><nobr>legal frameworks, stable macroeconomic conditions, competitive</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15356;left:453><nobr>procurement, strong commitment by both parties, clarity of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15374;left:453><nobr>roles and responsibilities among parties, financial capabilities</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15392;left:453><nobr>of the private sector, technological innovation, open and constant</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15410;left:453><nobr>communication, detailed project planning, and guarantees</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15428;left:453><nobr>provided by the government. For the classification of CSFs,</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15446;left:453><nobr><a href=#21>Jefferies (2006) </a><font color=#231f20>identified CSFs from different groups such as</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15464;left:453><nobr>project company, main contractors, investors, operators, and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15482;left:453><nobr>host government. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#19>Aerts et al. (2014) </a></font>divided the CSFs into</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15499;left:453><nobr>the following categories: economic, financial, legal, political,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15517;left:453><nobr>procedural, social, structural, and technical factors. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Liu et al.</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15535;left:453><nobr><a href=#21>(2015) </a><font color=#231f20>identified CSFs by the phases (initiation and planning,</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15553;left:453><nobr>procurement, and partnership) of PPP infrastructure projects.</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15571;left:453><nobr><a href=#20>Chou and Pramudawardhani (2015) </a><font color=#231f20>set up the following five</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15589;left:453><nobr>groups of CSFs: stable macroeconomic environment, shared</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15607;left:453><nobr>responsibility between public and private sectors, transparent</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15625;left:453><nobr>and efficient procurement process, stable political and social</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15643;left:453><nobr>environment, and judicious government control. Common with</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14598;left:49><nobr>12</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:14598;left:250><nobr><i>C. Cui et al. / International Journal of Project Management xx (2018) xxx</i>–<i>xxx</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15679;left:58><nobr>Please cite this article as: C. Cui, et al., 2018. Review of studies on the public–private partnerships (PPP) for infrastructure projects, Int. J. Proj. Manag. <font color=#2e3192><a href=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=vi&amp;prev=_t&amp;sl=auto&amp;tl=vi&amp;u=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004>https://doi.org/</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15693;left:58><nobr><a href=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=vi&amp;prev=_t&amp;sl=auto&amp;tl=vi&amp;u=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004>10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004</a></nobr></div>
