<div style=position:absolute;top:15716;left:0><hr><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td bgcolor=eeeeee align=right><font face=arial,sans-serif><a name=14><b>Page 14</b></a></font></td></tr></table></div><font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15829;left:64><nobr>studies on risk allocation, empirical research and associated</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15847;left:64><nobr>research methods are widely used in identifying CSFs.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15883;left:64><nobr><i>5.4. Group 4: procurement and contract management (G4)</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15918;left:82><nobr>This topic focuses on procurement tendering, key contract</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15936;left:64><nobr>clauses, and contract negotiation within the PPP framework.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15954;left:64><nobr>As showed in <font color=#2e3192><a href=#6>Table 2</a></font>, half of Tiong's studies are about</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15972;left:64><nobr>procurement tendering issues, which paved the foundation for the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15990;left:64><nobr>follow-up research and practice of PPP. Additionally, among</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16008;left:64><nobr>these 754 reviewed studies, all researches about tendering before</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16026;left:64><nobr>2000 were accomplished by Tiong's team. Tiong's research topic</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16044;left:64><nobr>about tendering focussed on technical solution in procurement</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16062;left:64><nobr>tendering such as competition, negotiation, risks, and guarantees.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16080;left:64><nobr>In the recent years, the focus on research topics about tendering</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16098;left:64><nobr>has shifted to completion efficiency of procurement tendering.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16116;left:64><nobr>Owing to this, PPPs are often characterised by lengthy tendering</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16134;left:64><nobr>periods compared to traditional procurement models. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Reeves and</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16151;left:64><nobr><a href=#22>Flannery (2015) </a><font color=#231f20>explored the complex array of factors that can</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16169;left:64><nobr>impact tendering periods; the study also aimed to explore means</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16187;left:64><nobr>to reduce the tendering period and deliver infrastructure on time</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16205;left:64><nobr>and within budget. The study also revealed the following factors</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16223;left:64><nobr>impacting the tendering period: significant sectoral variations</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16241;left:64><nobr>within projects, capital values, overlap with the timing of general</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16259;left:64><nobr>elections, and the competitive dialogue procurement method</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16277;left:64><nobr>(<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Reeves et al., 2017</a></font>). Considering that the success of PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16295;left:64><nobr>projects largely depends on the performance of tendering</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16313;left:64><nobr>processes, critical factors affecting the effectiveness and effi-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16331;left:64><nobr>ciency of PPP tendering were conducted (<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Liu et al., 2016b</a></font><a href=#21></a>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16349;left:82><nobr>Risk and reward are the key contract clauses that are subject</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16367;left:64><nobr>to repetitive negotiation in PPP projects. The concession period is</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16385;left:64><nobr>often considered a critical influencing factor for risk and reward</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16403;left:64><nobr>and can be determined by the development of quantitative models</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16420;left:64><nobr>and well-structured concessionaire selection frameworks (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Zhang</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16438;left:64><nobr><a href=#23>et al., 2002</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#23></a>) to protect the interests of both the government</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16456;left:64><nobr>and private investors. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Auriol and Picard (2013) </a></font>suggest that</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16474;left:64><nobr>asymmetries in the concession period can be impacted by</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16492;left:64><nobr>the shadow costs of public funds and information. Therefore, a</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16510;left:64><nobr>better understanding of what is important to each party during</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16528;left:64><nobr>negotiations forms an important step in improving the PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16546;left:64><nobr>process (<a href=#19></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#19>Ahadzi and Bowles, 2004</a></font><a href=#19></a>). To improve negotiation</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16564;left:64><nobr>efficiency, the game theory has been used to introduce the new</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16582;left:64><nobr>negotiation method in the BOT bargaining concession models</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16600;left:64><nobr>(<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Shen et al., 2007</a></font><a href=#22></a>) and to evaluate the efficiency of changing</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16618;left:64><nobr>strategies of negotiation when the project output is standardised</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16636;left:64><nobr>(<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Javed et al., 2014</a></font><a href=#21></a>). In addition, <font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Liou and Huang (2008) </a></font>proposed</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16654;left:64><nobr>an automated approach towards the negotiation of BOT contracts</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16672;left:64><nobr>using the Monte Carlo simulation model in which high- and low-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16690;left:64><nobr>risk scenarios were obtained to determine whether the contractual</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16707;left:64><nobr>negotiation models vary in accordance with the risk levels.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16725;left:82><nobr>Indeterminacy during long project concession periods and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16743;left:64><nobr>the incompleteness of many PPP contracts highlights the need</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16761;left:64><nobr>for an incomplete contract and contract renegotiation. In practice,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16779;left:64><nobr>incomplete contracts, which are most likely to be renegotiated,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16797;left:64><nobr>are popularly used in complex PPP projects, especially under the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16815;left:64><nobr>immature PPP market and corrupt institutional environments</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16833;left:64><nobr>(<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Iossa and Martimort, 2016</a></font>). Concerning the requirement of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15829;left:467><nobr>managerial flexibility, <font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Cruz and Marques (2013) </a></font>propose a</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15847;left:467><nobr>double entry matrix as a new model for contract flexibility.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15865;left:467><nobr>Likewise, <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Nikolaidis et al. (2013) </a></font>used a road concession case</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15883;left:467><nobr>under renegotiation to develop a concession renegotiation</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15900;left:467><nobr>framework that combines the estimation of stakeholder payoffs</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15918;left:467><nobr>with various available strategic options. Compensation models</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15936;left:467><nobr>for the three common compensation measures, namely, toll</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15954;left:467><nobr>adjustment, contract extension, and annual subsidy or unitary</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15972;left:467><nobr>payment adjustment, were examined by <font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Xiong and Zhang</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15990;left:467><nobr><a href=#23>(2014)</a><font color=#231f20>. Concerning why and how PPP contracts are renegotiated,</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16008;left:467><nobr>two case studies were examined by <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Sarmento and Renneboog</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16026;left:467><nobr><a href=#22>(2016)</a><font color=#231f20>. Incomplete contracts and flexible contracts are usually</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16044;left:467><nobr>designed under the assumption that there exist considerable</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16062;left:467><nobr>transaction costs of specifying more flexible contracts with</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16080;left:467><nobr>certain performance obligations in an uncertain environment.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16098;left:467><nobr>Compared to incomplete contracts, complete contracts allow</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16116;left:467><nobr>for lower transaction costs in the initial stage but incur higher</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16134;left:467><nobr>costs of establishing the terms of ex-post trade (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Domingues and</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16151;left:467><nobr><a href=#20>Zlatkovic, 2015</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#20></a>). The key contract clauses, contract negotiation,</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16169;left:467><nobr>incomplete contract, and renegotiation aim to improve the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16187;left:467><nobr>validity of a contract. Based on the trajectory of previous studies,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16205;left:467><nobr>we predict that approaches towards contract renegotiation and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16223;left:467><nobr>methods to improve the effect of a contract will continue to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16241;left:467><nobr>develop into a key research interest area under this topic in the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16259;left:467><nobr>future.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16295;left:467><nobr><i>5.5. Group 5: performance management (G5)</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16331;left:485><nobr>As shown in <font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Fig. 6</a></font><a href=#20></a>, the coverage of material sources for this</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16349;left:467><nobr>topic ranks the highest, hitting 24.3%. However, articles having</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16367;left:467><nobr>the word ‘performance’ in titles amount to 22, which only</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16385;left:467><nobr>accounts for 2.9% of the total 754 studies. This finding suggests</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16403;left:467><nobr>that while performance is the primary objective of PPP projects,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16420;left:467><nobr>the topic tends to focus on KPI and performance measurement.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16438;left:485><nobr>Studies that focus on performance have begun to appear</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16456;left:467><nobr>over the last decade. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Indridason and Wang (2008) </a></font>analysed the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16474;left:467><nobr>driving factors for job performance in PPP projects and found</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16492;left:467><nobr>that employee commitment proved to be an effective predicator</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16510;left:467><nobr>of citizenship behaviour and job performance. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Yuan et al.</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16528;left:467><nobr><a href=#23>(2009) </a><font color=#231f20>selected 15 performance objectives based on the goal-</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16546;left:467><nobr>setting theory and established a conceptual KPI framework;</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16564;left:467><nobr>this framework has been developed into a more detailed KPI</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16582;left:467><nobr>conceptual model composed of 41 indicators (<a href=#23></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Yuan et al.,</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16600;left:467><nobr><a href=#23>2012</a><font color=#231f20>). </font><a href=#21>Mladenovic et al. (2013) </a><font color=#231f20>conducted similar research</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16618;left:467><nobr>with <font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Yuan et al. (2009) </a></font>and introduced a two-layer approach for</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16636;left:467><nobr>the performance assessment of PPP projects. The performance</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16654;left:467><nobr>of PPP projects is usually evaluated on the basis of the time</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16672;left:467><nobr>and cost that is saved through the PPP model. Sometimes, it is</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16690;left:467><nobr>related not only to the project ‘input’ and ‘output’ but also to the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16704;left:467><nobr>‘process’ and ‘outcomes’ (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Liu et al., 2014a</a></font><a href=#21></a>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16725;left:485><nobr>Since conventional ex-post evaluation is not robust enough</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16743;left:467><nobr>to measure the performance of PPP projects, the lifecycle</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16761;left:467><nobr>(process-based) evaluation under the performance measurement</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16779;left:467><nobr>system has become a promising approach for comprehensive</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16797;left:467><nobr>and effective measurement of the PPP performance. The</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16815;left:467><nobr>building information model (BIM) was adopted using informa-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16833;left:467><nobr>tion technology to evaluate the performance of lifecycle</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15788;left:832><nobr>13</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:15788;left:264><nobr><i>C. Cui et al. / International Journal of Project Management xx (2018) xxx</i>–<i>xxx</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:16869;left:73><nobr>Please cite this article as: C. Cui, et al., 2018. Review of studies on the public–private partnerships (PPP) for infrastructure projects, Int. J. </span></font>
<font size=2 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>

<div style=position:absolute;top:16906;left:0><hr><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td bgcolor=eeeeee align=right><font face=arial,sans-serif><a name=15><b>Page 15</b></a></font></td></tr></table></div><font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17019;left:49><nobr>stakeholders in the future; this is because the model provides</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17037;left:49><nobr>digital representation of the physical and functional characteris-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17055;left:49><nobr>tics of an asset and enables key decision-makers to make</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17073;left:49><nobr>informed decisions across a project's lifecycle (<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Love et al., 2015</a></font>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17090;left:49><nobr>Such an approach may also assist PPP projects in meeting</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17108;left:49><nobr>sustainability criteria, which are increasingly being considered</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17126;left:49><nobr>as CSFs and are facilitating the achievement of project KPIs</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17144;left:49><nobr>(<font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Osei-Kyei and Chan, 2016</a></font><a href=#22></a>). Researchers also study different</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17162;left:49><nobr>features of performance measurement for special regions and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17180;left:49><nobr>types of projects (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Tawalare and Balu, 2016</a></font><a href=#22></a>). Comparative</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17198;left:49><nobr>research on performance measurement between different ap-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17216;left:49><nobr>proaches (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Villalba-Romero and Liyanage, 2016</a></font>) and different</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17234;left:49><nobr>project types (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Henjewele et al., 2014</a></font><a href=#21></a>) occupy a place in this</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17252;left:49><nobr>topic; we also predict that these research areas will gain</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17270;left:49><nobr>popularity in the future. In addition to the theoretical research,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17288;left:49><nobr>the practice of performance measurement in PPP project has been</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17306;left:49><nobr>studied, which shows that a process-based lifecycle performance</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17324;left:49><nobr>measurement together with VFM can improve traditional ex-ante</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17341;left:49><nobr>and ex-post evaluations.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17395;left:49><nobr><i>5.6. Group 6: governance and regulation (G6)</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17431;left:67><nobr>This topic focuses on the project governance and government</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17449;left:49><nobr>policy environment concerns for PPP projects. In some projects, a</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17467;left:49><nobr>mismatch is revealed between the complicated governance</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17485;left:49><nobr>approach and the relatively straightforward infrastructures that</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17503;left:49><nobr>were developed; this has led to the argument that a better sense</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17521;left:49><nobr>of contingency is required in future PPP programs (<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Hurk and</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17539;left:49><nobr><a href=#21>Verhoest, 2014</a><font color=#231f20>). With a focus on good governance, </font><a href=#20>Dunn-</a></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17557;left:49><nobr><a href=#20>Cavelty and Suter (2009) </a><font color=#231f20>set up an expanded governance model</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17575;left:49><nobr>for the critical infrastructure protection (CIP) and found that</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17593;left:49><nobr>policies should increasingly rely on self-regulating and self-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17610;left:49><nobr>organising networks. <font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Devapriya (2006) </a></font>analysed the theoretical</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17628;left:49><nobr>framework for funding in PPP organisations and found that</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17646;left:49><nobr>debt has not been effective in controlling managers' behaviour.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17664;left:49><nobr>This is because subordinate financing also serves to address</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17682;left:49><nobr>debt agency in the capital structure of those regulated PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17700;left:49><nobr>organisations. Evidence reveals that good governance institutions</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17718;left:49><nobr>and, specifically, good regulatory quality enhance PPP perfor-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17736;left:49><nobr>mance, apparent from the positive effect of good governance</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17754;left:49><nobr>institutions and good regulatory quality on investment growth</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17772;left:49><nobr>(<font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Sabry, 2015</a></font><a href=#22></a>). Proper risk allocation and the strategic approach</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17790;left:49><nobr>have enhanced the performance of PPP projects, which is related</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17808;left:49><nobr>to the development of good project governance (<a href=#19></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#19>Abednego and</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17826;left:49><nobr><a href=#19>Ogunlana, 2006</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#19></a>).</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17019;left:470><nobr>A series of effective methods and approaches were developed</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17037;left:453><nobr>to improve individual project governance efficiency; however,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17055;left:453><nobr>the constantly changing economy and frequent policy reforma-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17073;left:453><nobr>tion continuously alter the external environment of governance</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17090;left:453><nobr>mechanism. Therefore, researchers are studying key issues</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17108;left:453><nobr>in this area to maintain a clear understanding of project</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17126;left:453><nobr>governance. In addition to the fact that weak governance has a</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17144;left:453><nobr>damaging effect on a country's politics, economy, and public</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17162;left:453><nobr>administration, project governance often suffers from a lack of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17180;left:453><nobr>human, physical, and financial resources; poor interdepartmental</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17198;left:453><nobr>coordination; fraught relationships between central and local</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17216;left:453><nobr>governments; and political interference in day-to-day operations</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17234;left:453><nobr>(<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Bhuiyan, 2010</a></font><a href=#20></a>). The issues about project governance were</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17252;left:453><nobr>also identified across two dominant interfaces, one between the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17270;left:453><nobr>public and private sectors and the other between the project and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17288;left:453><nobr>societal stakeholders, which <font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Delhi et al. (2012) </a></font>suggest is typical</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17306;left:453><nobr>for infrastructure projects in India. The lack of legal definition of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17324;left:453><nobr>a PPP acts as a barrier to effective PPP management during the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17341;left:453><nobr>development of effective PPP legal frameworks. Controversy</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17359;left:453><nobr>over a government’s guarantee of legal status, bureaucratic</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17377;left:453><nobr>tariff setting for partnership services, non-existent opportunity for</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17395;left:453><nobr>private asset ownership, and excessive government regulation of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17413;left:453><nobr>PPP workers’ wage rates were all identified by <font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Mouraviev and</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17431;left:453><nobr><a href=#22>Kakabadse (2015)</a><font color=#231f20>.</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17449;left:470><nobr>Besides, since some infrastructures are considered public</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17467;left:453><nobr>goods, public governance mechanism and the method of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17485;left:453><nobr>implementing a PPP infrastructure project should be given</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17503;left:453><nobr>more attention in the future (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Zaato and Hudon, 2015</a></font><a href=#23></a>). To solve</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17521;left:453><nobr>the public governance problems experienced by many PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17539;left:453><nobr>projects, the development of government policies and government</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17557;left:453><nobr>regulations (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Rouhani et al., 2015</a></font>) was suggested as supportive</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17575;left:453><nobr>mechanisms that can improve governance performance.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17611;left:453><nobr><i>5.7. Relationship between different groups</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17647;left:470><nobr>These six research groups were further categorized based on</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17664;left:453><nobr>the theoretical foundations framework. Group 1 focussed on the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17682;left:453><nobr>nature and rationale for establishing PPPs and on the merit</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17700;left:453><nobr>and worth of PPPs. Group 2, Group 3, and Group 4 focussed</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17718;left:453><nobr>on decisions to undertake PPPs based on proper application</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17736;left:453><nobr>conditions, effective risk management, and flexible contract</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17754;left:453><nobr>management; however, Group 5 was related to ex-post evalua-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17772;left:453><nobr>tions of PPPs that aim to improve performance of PPP projects.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17790;left:453><nobr>Group 6 highlighted the importance of improving governance</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17808;left:453><nobr>and policies of PPP projects. Based on the lifecycle of PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:17826;left:453><nobr>implementation in infrastructure projects, the relationships</nobr></div>
</span></font>

<div style=position:absolute;top:18298;left:64><nobr>undertake PPPs and the ex-post evaluations of PPPs.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18335;left:64><nobr><b>6. Research gaps and research directions</b></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18370;left:82><nobr>As discussed above, the extant body of literature on PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18388;left:64><nobr>research has enabled advances in the practice of PPP infrastructure</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18406;left:64><nobr>projects. Nevertheless, there still are some problems and defi-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18424;left:64><nobr>ciencies in the PPP theory and practices pertaining to infrastruc-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18442;left:64><nobr>ture projects. To achieve success in PPP projects, the framework</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18460;left:64><nobr>in <font color=#2e3192><a href=#16>Fig. 8 </a></font>must be considered that indicates the effect of the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18478;left:64><nobr>research topics, which are summarised in recent research, as</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18496;left:64><nobr>well as the problems and deficiencies that are shown in dotted</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18514;left:64><nobr>lines. Concerning the decision process in PPPs, the economic</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18532;left:64><nobr>feasibility and value for money evaluations are the key methods</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18550;left:64><nobr>involved in the selection and scoping of PPP projects. This</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18567;left:64><nobr>selection does not consider public attitudes and other stake-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18585;left:64><nobr>holders' expectations. However, public opposition has been</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18603;left:64><nobr>reported as the main reason for the failure of PPP projects in some</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18621;left:64><nobr>instances (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Henjewele et al., 2013</a></font>). Because of great influence to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18639;left:64><nobr>VFM evaluation and economic feasibility evaluation, there needs</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18657;left:64><nobr>to be a focus on well-structured risk management and feasible</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18675;left:64><nobr>decision methods necessary to improve performance of PPPs</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18693;left:64><nobr>(<a href=#23></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Yuan et al., 2009</a></font>). Improving sustainability performance is an</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18711;left:64><nobr>important target when developing PPP infrastructure projects,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18729;left:64><nobr>and the sustainability quantitative appraisal still needs further</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18747;left:64><nobr>exploration to ascertain ways that can be employed to improve</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18765;left:64><nobr>the sustainability performance of PPP projects (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Shen et al., 2016</a></font><a href=#22></a>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18783;left:64><nobr>Owing to the changing nature of PPP projects, rigidity contracts</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18801;left:64><nobr>need ‘overwriting’ contract clauses to decrease the number of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18818;left:64><nobr>unexpected situations. Additionally, there needs to be a solution</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18836;left:64><nobr>on facilitating the establishment of flexible contracts (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Cruz and</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18209;left:467><nobr><a href=#20>Marques, 2013</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#20></a>). Additionally, the efficiency of contract negoti-</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18227;left:467><nobr>ation and renegotiation in facilitating flexible contracts should</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18245;left:467><nobr>also be explored and improved in the future (<a href=#23></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Xiong and Zhang,</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18263;left:467><nobr><a href=#23>2016</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#23></a>). PPPs' inefficiency is sometimes attributed to deficient</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18280;left:467><nobr>regulation and overregulation of the government, while a way to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18298;left:467><nobr>achieve efficiency in PPP governance should be highlighted as a</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18316;left:467><nobr>topic for future research (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Mouraviev and Kakabadse, 2015</a></font>). In</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18334;left:467><nobr>summary, the main body of knowledge for PPP and guidance</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18352;left:467><nobr>on PPP projects implementation, research on how to manage</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18370;left:467><nobr>knowledge, and filling the apparent knowledge gaps in PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18388;left:467><nobr>projects remain relatively underdeveloped (<a href=#19></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#19>Aerts et al., 2017</a></font>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18406;left:467><nobr>In summary, this review identifies research gaps and research</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18424;left:467><nobr>directions as follows.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18460;left:467><nobr><i>6.1. Social impact assessment for project selection</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18496;left:485><nobr>Private participation in infrastructure projects can sometimes</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18514;left:467><nobr>improve quality and expand the coverage of key public services.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18532;left:467><nobr>The economic feasibility and VFM evaluations are key methods</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18550;left:467><nobr>involved in the selection and scoping of PPP projects, which</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18567;left:467><nobr>pay more attention to economic effects rather than social</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18585;left:467><nobr>effects. Despite this, PPP projects often attract public and other</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18603;left:467><nobr>stakeholders' opposition because of perceived lower quality,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18621;left:467><nobr>higher price, and lower-than-expected private sector perfor-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18639;left:467><nobr>mance (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Ameyaw and Chan, 2013</a></font><a href=#20></a>). Public opposition has been</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18657;left:467><nobr>reported as the main reason for the failure of PPP projects</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18675;left:467><nobr>in some instances (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Henjewele et al., 2013</a></font><a href=#21></a>); however, public</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18693;left:467><nobr>attitudes and expectations have not received much consideration</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18711;left:467><nobr>during the decision process for PPPs. Physical infrastructure is a</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18729;left:467><nobr>basic requirement that ensures smooth functioning of economic</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18747;left:467><nobr>and social life. Hence, lack of proper infrastructure creates</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18765;left:467><nobr>grounds wherein infrastructure projects are subject to strong</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18783;left:467><nobr>external forces such as attracting public distrust. However, this</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18801;left:467><nobr>negative aspect is offset by the potential of such projects to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18818;left:467><nobr>improve travel convenience, raise living standards, and improve</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18836;left:467><nobr>employment rates.</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19215;left:313><nobr>Fig. 8. Research gaps framework based on research topics.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:18168;left:832><nobr>15</nobr></div>

Proj. Manag. <font color=#2e3192><a href=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=vi&amp;prev=_t&amp;sl=auto&amp;tl=vi&amp;u=https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ijproman.2018.03.004>https://doi.org/</a></font></nobr></div>

<div style=position:absolute;top:19286;left:0><hr><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td bgcolor=eeeeee align=right><font face=arial,sans-serif><a name=17><b>Page 17</b></a></font></td></tr></table></div><font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19399;left:67><nobr>There have been many existing methodologies and tech-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19417;left:49><nobr>niques to select appropriate projects where PPP can deliver</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19435;left:49><nobr>more efficient outputs, such as financial evaluation, economic</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19453;left:49><nobr>evaluation, and value for money assessment. Social impact</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19470;left:49><nobr>assessment is significant for PPP projects, but has been largely</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19488;left:49><nobr>ignored during the development of PPP projects and is given</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19506;left:49><nobr>little coverage in academic studies. As a popular PPP project</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19524;left:49><nobr>selection method, VFM assessments focus on the economic</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19542;left:49><nobr>effects of projects in isolation. To improve PPP project</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19560;left:49><nobr>selection methods, social impact evaluation systems should be</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19578;left:49><nobr>established to identify and evaluate the differences of social</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19596;left:49><nobr>impact between traditional procurement and PPP. We suggest</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19614;left:49><nobr>that social impact should be considered and evaluated prior to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19632;left:49><nobr>project selection, according to different applications of PPP in</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19650;left:49><nobr>the infrastructure domain. The study of social impact evaluation</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19668;left:49><nobr>indicators and evaluation methods should become a mainstream</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19686;left:49><nobr>feature of research in this area to fill this gap.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19704;left:67><nobr>Furthermore, environmental impact assessment systems should</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19721;left:49><nobr>become an integral part of the PPP project selection process. In</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19739;left:49><nobr>view of the long lifecycle and long-term impact on the local</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19757;left:49><nobr>finance of PPP projects, intergenerational impact effects should be</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19775;left:49><nobr>evaluated. We predict that the evaluation process, index, method,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19793;left:49><nobr>standard of social impact, environmental impact, and intergener-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19811;left:49><nobr>ational impact on PPP projects will attract the attention of many</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19829;left:49><nobr>researchers in the future.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19865;left:49><nobr><i>6.2. Efficient risk management to perfect the PPP decision</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19883;left:49><nobr><i>process</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19919;left:67><nobr>Exiting great influence to value for money evaluation and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19937;left:49><nobr>economic feasibility evaluation, risk evaluation and allocation</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19955;left:49><nobr>also impact performance of PPPs directly. In PPP projects,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19973;left:49><nobr>it is understood that VFM should include initial cost, risks</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19990;left:49><nobr>assessment, and competitive neutrality with qualitative and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20008;left:49><nobr>quantitative techniques (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Ameyaw et al., 2015</a></font>). A comprehen-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20026;left:49><nobr>sive evaluation and reasonable allocation of risks will help</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20044;left:49><nobr>forestall any future stakeholder agitation against PPP projects</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20062;left:49><nobr>(<font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Pitt et al., 2006</a></font><a href=#22></a>). Researchers have taken further steps to ensure</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20080;left:49><nobr>greater transparency in the VFM assessment by introducing</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20098;left:49><nobr>workshops that bring experts, public officials, and consultants to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20116;left:49><nobr>identify and categorise risks, allocate risks, estimate probability</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20134;left:49><nobr>and cost, and quantify risk value (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Ameyaw et al., 2015</a></font>). There</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20152;left:49><nobr>still are some high-risk influences (e.g. political risks and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20170;left:49><nobr>usage risks) in PPP projects that can negatively impact VFM</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20188;left:49><nobr>achievement (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Henjewele et al., 2011</a></font><a href=#20></a>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20206;left:67><nobr>The researchers must assess the considerable risks that</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20224;left:49><nobr>emerge from the considerable uncertainties in the infrastructure</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20242;left:49><nobr>projects. Successful project implementation during the entire</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20260;left:49><nobr>lifecycle of a project would clearly demand effective manage-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20277;left:49><nobr>ment and proper allocation of risk. Systematic risks would</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20295;left:49><nobr>be allocated to the sector that can manage it more effectively</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20313;left:49><nobr>to maximize the chance of improving the performance of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20331;left:49><nobr>PPP projects (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Wamuziri and Clearie, 2005</a></font>). To improve risk</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20349;left:49><nobr>evaluation and risk allocation methods, we suggest that the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20367;left:49><nobr>identification and evaluation of risks should be quantified</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20385;left:49><nobr>systematically and individually based on the nature of project</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20403;left:49><nobr>type, project implementation stage, and background of the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19399;left:453><nobr>project location, among others. The study of well-structured</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19417;left:453><nobr>risk management and feasible decision methods should become</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19435;left:453><nobr>a mainstream feature of research in this area as a means to fill</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19453;left:453><nobr>the stated gap.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19506;left:453><nobr><i>6.3. Performance appraisal criterion for the sustainability of</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19524;left:453><nobr><i>PPP projects</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19560;left:470><nobr>Private sector not only provides funding for infrastructure</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19578;left:453><nobr>projects but also contributes its expertise towards engendering</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19596;left:453><nobr>innovation and developing a sustainable asset. Hence, improving</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19614;left:453><nobr>sustainability performance should be an important target for</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19632;left:453><nobr>developing PPP infrastructure projects. Sustainability perfor-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19650;left:453><nobr>mance appraisal of PPP projects has attracted several researchers</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19668;left:453><nobr>who aimed to perfect economic, social, and environmental</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19686;left:453><nobr>performance criteria in examining project feasibility (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Shen et al.,</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19704;left:453><nobr><a href=#22>2016</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#22></a>). Various effective appraisal models and useful methods for</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19721;left:453><nobr>optimising have been proposed, and sustainable assets of various</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19739;left:453><nobr>types of infrastructure projects with improved maintenance have</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19757;left:453><nobr>been set up to improve the theory and method of sustainability</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19775;left:453><nobr>performance appraisal of PPP projects (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Love et al., 2015</a></font><a href=#21></a>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19793;left:453><nobr>Sustainable development, sustainable viability, and sustainable</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19811;left:453><nobr>profitability have proved to be the most highly emphasised</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19829;left:453><nobr>indicators in performance management and in the measurement</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19847;left:453><nobr>of PPP projects (<a href=#23></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Yuan et al., 2012</a></font><a href=#23></a>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19865;left:470><nobr>However, there is still a lack of formal, systematic, and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19883;left:453><nobr>operational measures to evaluate the PPP performance if</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19901;left:453><nobr>the outputs are sustainable for a long-term contractual period</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19919;left:453><nobr>(<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>liu et al., 2016a</a></font><a href=#21></a>). The delivery of VFM should rely on long-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19937;left:453><nobr>term project performance at a high level, which would</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19955;left:453><nobr>sustainably benefit the expanded development of PPPs</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19973;left:453><nobr>(<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Sobhiyah et al., 2009</a></font>). Nevertheless, in some PPP projects,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19990;left:453><nobr>the overall cost to achieve the perceived positive performance is</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20008;left:453><nobr>unsustainable. Some projects broaden the scope during</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20026;left:453><nobr>implementation in response to the new sustainability agenda;</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20044;left:453><nobr>this resulted in inconsistent performance of infrastructure</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20062;left:453><nobr>projects (<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Henjewele et al., 2014</a></font><a href=#21></a>). Therefore, the key to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20080;left:453><nobr>achieving real sustainable performance lies in recognising the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20098;left:453><nobr>entire responsibility, undertaking a comprehensive analysis,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20116;left:453><nobr>and proposing acceptable price from the very beginning of PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20134;left:453><nobr>projects (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Hodge and Greve, 2007</a></font><a href=#21></a>). Additionally, minute details</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20152;left:453><nobr>that involve the sustainability and persistence of PPP projects</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20170;left:453><nobr>should be considered (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Páez-Pérez and Sánchez-Silva, 2016</a></font>). In</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20188;left:453><nobr>addition, the PPP project proponents should make an adequate</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20206;left:453><nobr>and sustained marketing campaign to ensure that the publics</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20224;left:453><nobr>can be creative in designing financial packages and in resource</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20242;left:453><nobr>allocation to improve PPP performance and sustain competitive</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20259;left:453><nobr>advantage (<a href=#23></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Yuan et al., 2009</a></font>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20277;left:470><nobr>In response to the lack of performance appraisal criterion for</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20295;left:453><nobr>sustainability of PPP projects, suggestions for future research</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20313;left:453><nobr>are as follows: (1) Sustainability quantitative appraisal criterion</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20331;left:453><nobr>still needs further exploration, and studies must be conducted to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20349;left:453><nobr>examine ways of improving the sustainability performance of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20367;left:453><nobr>PPP projects; (2) Sustainable marketing campaign environment</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20385;left:453><nobr>should be the main focus of future research; and (3) sustainability</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20403;left:453><nobr>performance must be maintained during the whole period and</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19358;left:49><nobr>16</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:19358;left:250><nobr><i>C. Cui et al. / International Journal of Project Management xx (2018) xxx</i>–<i>xxx</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20439;left:58><nobr>Please cite this article as: C. Cui, et al., 2018. Review of studies on the public–private partnerships (PPP) for infrastructure projects, Int. J. <div style=position:absolute;top:20476;left:0><hr><table border=0 width=100%><tr><td bgcolor=eeeeee align=right><font face=arial,sans-serif><a name=18><b>Page 18</b></a></font></td></tr></table></div><font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20589;left:64><nobr>minute details that involve the sustainability of a PPP project</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20607;left:64><nobr>should be considered in future research.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20643;left:64><nobr><i>6.4. Improved methodology for flexible contracting</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20678;left:82><nobr>PPP contracts are long-lasting and constantly changing. The</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20696;left:64><nobr>rigidity of contracts suggests that they are unable to adapt to great</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20714;left:64><nobr>uncertainty during the lifecycle of a PPP project. This has led</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20732;left:64><nobr>many practitioners to invest enormous efforts in ‘overwriting’</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20750;left:64><nobr>contracts to decrease the number of unexpected situations (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Cruz</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20768;left:64><nobr><a href=#20>and Marques, 2013</a><font color=#231f20><a href=#20></a>). Flexible contracts are more suitable when</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20786;left:64><nobr>it comes to dealing with uncertainty, and represent a sensible</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20804;left:64><nobr>approach for PPP projects. As per findings, only 10 out of the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20822;left:64><nobr>existing 754 studies employ methodologies to show how to</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20840;left:64><nobr>establish a flexible contract and how to concede in renegotiation.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20858;left:82><nobr>Although the terms of ‘flexible contract’ and ‘renegotiation’</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20876;left:64><nobr>introduce various alternative methodologies or guidelines,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20894;left:64><nobr>they are still at a nascent stage and offer enormous scope</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20911;left:64><nobr>for refinement. Among these 10 studies, 8 studies focus on</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20929;left:64><nobr>renegotiation methods and processes, while 2 studies focus</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20947;left:64><nobr>on renegotiation triggers and contractual flexibility analysis.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20965;left:64><nobr>Unlike suggestions on how to deal retrospectively with</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20983;left:64><nobr>renegotiation following a PPP contract conflict during the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21001;left:64><nobr>lifecycle of a PPP project, proactive measures, such as analysis</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21019;left:64><nobr>of renegotiation triggers and flexible contract terms before</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21037;left:64><nobr>contract conflict, have attracted little attention of scholars.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21055;left:64><nobr>This could be because many stakeholders of PPP projects pay</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21073;left:64><nobr>more attention towards protecting their interests, rather than</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21091;left:64><nobr>benefitting the overall project when contract conflicts occur.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21109;left:64><nobr>Concerning the use of methods, the game and real option</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21127;left:64><nobr>theories have been more frequently used; however, the win–</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21145;left:64><nobr>win theory and synergy theory have garnered lesser attention,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21163;left:64><nobr>despite their apparent applicability to PPP project management.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21180;left:64><nobr>Essentially, considering both stakeholders' interest and pro-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21198;left:64><nobr>ject’s success, we suggest that an important area of research</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21216;left:64><nobr>should be to combine strengths from existing methodologies</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21234;left:64><nobr>to explore contract flexibility classification and measurement,</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21252;left:64><nobr>flexible contract terms, dynamic contract supervision, and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21270;left:64><nobr>renegotiation triggers, among others. In addition, the lack of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21288;left:64><nobr>targeted research on different types of infrastructure projects and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21306;left:64><nobr>specific regions can lead to incomplete or inaccurate frameworks</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21324;left:64><nobr>for flexible contracts. Further research across these various</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21342;left:64><nobr>project types and regions are necessary to expedite renegotiation</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21360;left:64><nobr>frameworks and build flexible contract application.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21378;left:82><nobr>In response to the lack of a mature methodology for flexible</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21396;left:64><nobr>contracting, suggestions for future research are as follows:</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21414;left:64><nobr>(1) Private sector companies play an important role in PPP</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21432;left:64><nobr>application. The private sector must explore the method of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21450;left:64><nobr>partner selection and the assessment of their competency in the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21467;left:64><nobr>future; (2) As the main target of contract management, the cost</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21485;left:64><nobr>of negotiation and renegotiation during the full lifecycle of a</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21503;left:64><nobr>project should be scientifically reduced. Alongside this, the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21521;left:64><nobr>efficiency of contract negotiation and renegotiation in achieving</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21539;left:64><nobr>flexible contracts should be explored and improved in the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21557;left:64><nobr>future; and (3) Despite several real and perceived obstacles, we</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21575;left:64><nobr>suggest that perfecting the mechanism of flexible contracting</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21593;left:64><nobr>should remain the main focus of future research. It should also</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20589;left:467><nobr>include specific topics, such as contract terms, trigger condi-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20607;left:467><nobr>tions, renegotiation time-points, and other associated criteria.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20643;left:467><nobr><i>6.5. Government supervision of PPP projects</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20678;left:485><nobr>Governments support the development of PPPs with clear</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20696;left:467><nobr>policies, political commitment, and appropriate legal and regu-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20714;left:467><nobr>lative frameworks, which provide a stable and reasonable</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20732;left:467><nobr>cooperation environment for the public and private sectors.</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20750;left:467><nobr>Moreover, trust between public and private actors is fostered</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20768;left:467><nobr>by clear regulations, standards, clear roles of public actors, and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20786;left:467><nobr>ex-ante evaluation (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Verhoest et al., 2015</a></font><a href=#22></a>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20804;left:485><nobr>Good governance institutions, specifically good regulatory</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20822;left:467><nobr>quality, bureaucratic efficiency, and independence, enhance</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20840;left:467><nobr>PPP performance; this is evident from their positive effect</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20858;left:467><nobr>on investment growth. However, the lack of certain critical</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20876;left:467><nobr>ingredients of good governance has a direct and negative</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20894;left:467><nobr>impact on the fulfilment of PPP potential (<a href=#20></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Hayllar, 2010</a></font><a href=#20></a>). Good</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20911;left:467><nobr>governance and regulatory quality have become important</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20929;left:467><nobr>governance variables to facilitate private investment and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20947;left:467><nobr>improve the capability of governments (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Sabry, 2015</a></font><a href=#22></a>). During</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20965;left:467><nobr>the long-term contractual period of PPP projects, changing</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:20983;left:467><nobr>government regulation can lead to a difficulty in managing</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21001;left:467><nobr>diverse risks associated with government actions and supervi-</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21019;left:467><nobr>sion difficulty (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#23>Wibowo and Alfen, 2015</a></font>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21037;left:485><nobr>Regulatory quality should focus on not only irregularities</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21055;left:467><nobr>in the PPP legal framework and overregulation of government</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21073;left:467><nobr>but also focus on flexible supervision and the regulation of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21091;left:467><nobr>government. We suggest the following to improve the regulatory</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21109;left:467><nobr>quality of PPP projects. First, practitioners and researchers should</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21127;left:467><nobr>emphasise on deregulation trends of government to transform the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21145;left:467><nobr>regulatory landscape of infrastructure projects and strengthen</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21163;left:467><nobr>collaborative partnerships between industries and regulators and</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21180;left:467><nobr>other policymakers (<a href=#21></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#21>Koliba et al., 2014</a></font>). Second, practitioners</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21198;left:467><nobr>and researchers have to be concerned with ways to reduce the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21216;left:467><nobr>government’s overregulation of private operators; this might lead</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21234;left:467><nobr>to greater PPP flexibility in management and, ultimately, higher</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21252;left:467><nobr>efficiency when delivering the public services (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Mouraviev and</a></font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#2e3192 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#2e3192>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21270;left:467><nobr><a href=#22>Kakabadse, 2015</a><font color=#231f20>). Third, subsequent PPP studies must examine</font></nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=3 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:12px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21288;left:467><nobr>the policy diffusion and transfer processes from a formal to an</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21306;left:467><nobr>informal framework to understand the spread of PPP-supporting</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21324;left:467><nobr>policies, regulations, and other arrangements and to understand</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21342;left:467><nobr>how these elements serve as barriers to the development of</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21360;left:467><nobr>infrastructure PPPs (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Verhoest et al., 2015</a></font>).</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21396;left:467><nobr><i>6.6. Knowledge management methods for PPP projects</i></nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21432;left:485><nobr>Concerning public sector actors within PPP projects, state</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21450;left:467><nobr>and local governments possess little experience of working</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21467;left:467><nobr>in PPPs (<font color=#2e3192><a href=#20>Boyer, 2016</a></font><a href=#20></a>). Although some national or regional</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21485;left:467><nobr>level offices for collating lessons learnt and advising on the</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21503;left:467><nobr>implementation of PPPs have been established in some</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21521;left:467><nobr>developed countries, there is still an urgent need for more</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21539;left:467><nobr>training related to the development of PPPs, particularly among</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21557;left:467><nobr>the public sector procurement teams (<a href=#22></a><font color=#2e3192><a href=#22>Wang et al., 2016</a></font><a href=#22></a>). A</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21575;left:467><nobr>more developed and complete knowledge management system</nobr></div>
<div style=position:absolute;top:21593;left:467><nobr>could provide a baseline and reference standard to check skills</nobr></div>
</span></font>
<font size=2 color=#231f20 face=Times><span style=font-size:9px;font-family:Times;color:#231f20>
